<?php
$bodies = [
4825 => '<p>Choosing the right insulated garage door comes down to four things: the insulation type, the R-value, the door material, and how you actually use your garage. Get those four right and the door will keep your garage more comfortable for decades. We install insulated doors every week, and this is how we walk homeowners through the decision.</p>
<h2>What insulation types are available?</h2>
<p>Most insulated garage doors use one of two materials.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Polystyrene</strong> comes in rigid panels that fit inside the door sections. It costs less and adds a modest amount of thermal resistance. It is a solid choice for a garage you mostly use for parking.</li>
<li><strong>Polyurethane</strong> is foam injected between the steel skins of the door. It expands to fill every gap, bonds to the panels, and delivers more insulating power per inch. It also stiffens the door, which makes it quieter and more dent resistant.</li>
</ul>
<p>If you spend real time in the garage, or if there is living space above or beside it, polyurethane is usually worth the upgrade.</p>
<h2>How much R-value do you need?</h2>
<p>R-value measures resistance to heat flow. A higher number means better insulation. There is no single correct number for every home, but the pattern we see is simple. A detached garage used only for parking needs less. An attached garage that shares walls with your kitchen or has a bedroom above it benefits from a higher R-value, because that door is effectively part of your home\'s thermal envelope.</p>
<p>Keep in mind that R-value only tells part of the story. A well insulated door with sloppy gaps around it still leaks air. Construction quality, panel joints, and perimeter seals matter just as much as the number on the brochure.</p>
<h2>Which door material should you pick?</h2>
<p>Insulation lives inside the door, but the skin you choose affects durability, looks, and maintenance.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Steel</strong> is the most common choice. A double or triple layer steel door sandwiches the insulation between tough skins and needs very little upkeep.</li>
<li><strong>Wood</strong> looks beautiful and insulates naturally, but it needs regular refinishing and weighs more.</li>
<li><strong>Aluminum and glass</strong> doors give a modern look. Insulated glass helps, but these doors generally trail steel on thermal performance.</li>
<li><strong>Composite and faux wood</strong> doors mimic real wood grain over an insulated core, giving you the look without the maintenance.</li>
</ul>
<h2>How does your garage use change the answer?</h2>
<p>Be honest about what happens in your garage. If it is a workshop, a gym, or a laundry space, treat it like a room and insulate accordingly. If a bedroom sits above the garage, an insulated door noticeably evens out the temperature in that room. If the garage is detached and only holds a mower, a basic insulated door or even a non-insulated door may be all you need.</p>
<p>Also think about noise. Insulated doors run quieter because the foam dampens vibration. On a home where the garage is under a living area, that alone sells the upgrade for many of our customers.</p>
<h2>What else should you check before buying?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Perimeter sealing.</strong> Ask about the bottom seal and the weatherstripping package. A tight perimeter protects the insulation investment.</li>
<li><strong>Thermal breaks.</strong> Better doors separate the inner and outer skins so heat cannot travel straight through the steel.</li>
<li><strong>Springs sized for the door.</strong> Insulated doors weigh more, so the counterbalance system must be matched to the new weight. This is a job for a pro, and it is part of every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> we do.</li>
<li><strong>Wind load and durability.</strong> Foam filled doors resist flexing and dents better, which matters for busy households.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Should you match the door to your climate?</h2>
<p>Yes. In a cold climate, insulation pays off most in winter, keeping the garage warmer and reducing the load on any heated rooms nearby. In hot months the same door slows heat gain, so the garage does not turn into an oven by mid afternoon. Homes that see both extremes get value from the door all year, which is why insulated doors are our default recommendation for attached garages in this part of the country.</p>
<h2>Ready to compare doors side by side?</h2>
<p>You can preview styles, colors, and window options on your own photo of your home using our <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a>. When you have a shortlist, we will measure the opening, talk through insulation levels, and give you a straight recommendation for your house and budget. <a href="/contact-us/">Reach out to Twins Garage Doors</a> and we will help you choose a door you will be happy with for the long haul.</p>',
4826 => '<p>An insulated garage door helps the environment in one main way: it reduces the energy your home wastes. A garage with a steady temperature leaks less heat from the house in winter and absorbs less heat in summer, so your furnace and air conditioner work less. Less energy burned means a smaller footprint, and the benefits stack up over the life of the door.</p>
<h2>How does an insulated door cut energy waste?</h2>
<p>Most attached garages share at least one wall with living space, and many sit under bedrooms. When the garage swings between freezing and sweltering, the rooms around it follow. Your HVAC system then spends extra energy fighting that swing.</p>
<p>An insulated door slows heat transfer through the largest opening in the garage. The garage stays closer to a moderate temperature, the shared walls and ceiling lose less conditioned air, and your heating and cooling equipment runs fewer cycles. The door does not need power to do this. It works passively, every hour of every day.</p>
<h2>Why does a longer lasting door matter for the environment?</h2>
<p>Manufacturing any door consumes raw materials and energy. A door that lasts longer spreads that manufacturing impact over more years of service.</p>
<p>Insulated doors tend to outlast basic single layer doors because the foam core bonds the skins together into a stiffer, stronger panel. That structure resists dents, flexing, and sagging. Fewer replacement doors over the life of your home means less steel produced, less freight, and less old material heading to disposal.</p>
<h2>Does an insulated door reduce noise pollution too?</h2>
<p>It does, and people forget this one. The foam core dampens vibration, so the door opens and closes more quietly. It also blocks outside noise from entering the garage and any sound from a garage workshop from bothering the neighborhood. Quieter operation is a small thing, but it is a real quality of life improvement for your household and the houses around you.</p>
<h2>What role do seals play in the environmental picture?</h2>
<p>Insulation handles heat moving through the door. Seals handle air moving around it. The two work as a team.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bottom seal:</strong> closes the gap between the door and the floor.</li>
<li><strong>Perimeter weatherstripping:</strong> seals the sides and top of the opening.</li>
<li><strong>Section joints:</strong> good doors use interlocking joints that limit air leakage between panels.</li>
</ul>
<p>If the seals are cracked or flattened, cold drafts pour in and undo much of what the insulation accomplishes. Keeping seals fresh is one of the cheapest efficiency upgrades in the whole house, and it is a quick fix during any <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> visit.</p>
<h2>Can one door really make a difference?</h2>
<p>One door on one house is a small piece of the puzzle. But the garage door is usually the single largest moving object on a home and one of its biggest uninsulated surfaces. Upgrading it is one of the few improvements that touches such a large area in a single project. Multiply that across a neighborhood and the saved energy becomes meaningful. On your own utility bill, the effect shows up as a garage that no longer drags down the rooms attached to it.</p>
<h2>Are there greener choices within insulated doors?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Steel content.</strong> Steel doors commonly contain recycled steel, and steel is recyclable again at end of life.</li>
<li><strong>Polyurethane cores.</strong> Injected foam delivers high insulating value from a thin layer, so you get more performance per unit of material.</li>
<li><strong>Durable finishes.</strong> Factory baked finishes last for years without repainting, which means fewer coats of paint and solvents over the door\'s life.</li>
<li><strong>Right sized springs and hardware.</strong> A properly balanced door strains the opener less, extending the life of the motor and reducing replacement parts.</li>
</ul>
<h2>How do you get the most out of the upgrade?</h2>
<p>Pair the door with good habits. Keep the door closed when you are not using the garage. Have the seals inspected when they look worn. Keep the door balanced and lubricated so it closes fully and evenly. A door that sits crooked or reverses before closing leaves gaps that leak air, so small mechanical problems have an efficiency cost too.</p>
<p>If you are weighing an upgrade, we are glad to talk through insulation options and show you what fits your home during a <a href="/garage-door-installation/">new door installation</a>. Give Twins Garage Doors a call and we will help you pick a door that is easier on your bills and lighter on the environment.</p>',
4827 => '<p>Insulated garage doors come down to two core materials, polystyrene and polyurethane, wrapped in a skin of steel, wood, aluminum, or composite. Which combination you choose determines how warm the garage stays, how quiet the door runs, and how long it lasts. Here is what each material actually does, from a crew that installs them for a living.</p>
<h2>What is inside an insulated garage door?</h2>
<p>Think of an insulated door as a sandwich. The outer skin faces the weather. The core provides insulation. The inner skin finishes the back and adds rigidity. Doors are described by how many layers they have.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Single layer:</strong> one sheet of steel, no insulation. Light and inexpensive.</li>
<li><strong>Double layer:</strong> a steel skin with insulation attached behind it, often faced with a vinyl or fiberboard back.</li>
<li><strong>Triple layer:</strong> insulation fully enclosed between two steel skins. The strongest, quietest, and most efficient construction.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Polystyrene or polyurethane: what is the difference?</h2>
<p><strong>Polystyrene</strong> is the rigid foam you know from coolers and packaging. It arrives as pre-formed panels that slot into the door sections. Because the panels are cut to shape rather than molded in place, small air gaps can remain, and the insulating value per inch is lower. The trade-off is price. Polystyrene doors cost less and still beat an uninsulated door by a wide margin.</p>
<p><strong>Polyurethane</strong> is injected into the door as a liquid that expands into foam, filling every corner of the section and bonding to both skins. That gives it two advantages. First, more insulating value in the same thickness. Second, structure. The cured foam glues the sandwich together, so the door resists dents, bends, and road noise. If you want the best thermal and acoustic performance, polyurethane is the answer.</p>
<h2>How do the outer materials compare?</h2>
<h3>Steel</h3>
<p>Steel is the workhorse. It takes embossed wood grain textures, holds factory finishes for years, and pairs with either foam type. Thicker gauge skins shrug off dents better. For most homes, an insulated steel door is the best mix of cost, durability, and efficiency.</p>
<h3>Wood</h3>
<p>Wood offers natural beauty and decent inherent insulation, and custom builders can add core insulation as well. The cost is maintenance. Wood needs staining or painting on a regular schedule, and it is heavy, which demands properly sized springs.</p>
<h3>Aluminum and glass</h3>
<p>Full view aluminum doors look stunning on modern homes. Insulated glass panes and thermally improved rails help, but glass will never match a foam filled steel section. We recommend these doors for style first, efficiency second.</p>
<h3>Composite and faux wood</h3>
<p>Composite overlays and molded skins deliver the wood look over an insulated steel or foam core. You get curb appeal without the refinishing schedule. These have become one of our most requested categories.</p>
<h2>What is R-value and how much should you care?</h2>
<p>R-value measures resistance to heat flow, and higher is better. Use it to compare doors, but read the fine print. Some manufacturers quote the R-value at the center of a panel, which is the best spot on the door. Real world performance depends on the whole assembly: section joints, thermal breaks between skins, and the seals around the opening. A mid R-value door with tight joints and good weatherstripping can outperform a high R-value door installed poorly. Installation quality matters, which is why we treat sealing as part of every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a>.</p>
<h2>Which combination is right for your garage?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Detached garage, parking only:</strong> single layer or polystyrene double layer keeps costs down.</li>
<li><strong>Attached garage:</strong> polystyrene at minimum. The door is part of your home\'s envelope.</li>
<li><strong>Living space above or beside the garage:</strong> triple layer polyurethane. The comfort difference in those rooms is noticeable.</li>
<li><strong>Workshop, gym, or hobby space:</strong> triple layer polyurethane, plus attention to perimeter seals.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What about the parts you cannot see?</h2>
<p>Heavier insulated doors need springs, hinges, and tracks rated for the weight. Reusing old hardware on a new, heavier door causes premature wear and balance problems, and a door that slams or struggles is hard on the opener too. If your current door already binds or feels heavy, have it looked at before it fails. Our <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair team</a> sees the consequences of mismatched hardware all the time.</p>
<p>Want to see how different materials look on your actual house? Try our <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a>, then call Twins Garage Doors. We will help you match the core, the skin, and the hardware to how you really use your garage.</p>',
4828 => '<p>The secret behind energy-efficient garage doors is not one feature. It is a system: an insulated core, thermal breaks that stop heat from short-circuiting through the frame, and tight seals around the entire perimeter. When those three work together, the garage holds a steadier temperature and the rooms around it get easier to heat and cool.</p>
<h2>Why does garage door efficiency matter at all?</h2>
<p>The garage door is usually the largest opening in your home. If it is a thin sheet of uninsulated steel, it behaves like a giant radiator, dumping heat out in winter and soaking it in all summer. For attached garages, that thermal swing bleeds into the house through shared walls and ceilings. Your HVAC pays the bill. An efficient door quiets that whole cycle down.</p>
<h2>What makes up an energy-efficient door?</h2>
<h3>The insulated core</h3>
<p>Efficient doors put foam between their skins. Polystyrene panels offer good performance at a friendly price. Injected polyurethane fills the section completely, insulates better per inch, and stiffens the door. R-value is the comparison number, and higher means more resistance to heat flow. For attached garages and any garage with living space above it, more is better.</p>
<h3>Thermal breaks</h3>
<p>Steel conducts heat extremely well, which is a problem when the inner and outer skins of a door touch. A thermal break is a strip of non-conductive material separating those skins, so heat cannot travel straight through the metal. Doors without thermal breaks lose performance in ways the R-value sticker never shows. It is one of the first construction details we point out when customers compare quotes.</p>
<h3>Perimeter seals</h3>
<p>Air leaks defeat insulation. Efficient doors seal on all four sides:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bottom seal</strong> on an aluminum retainer, conforming to the floor.</li>
<li><strong>Side and top weatherstripping</strong> closing the gap between door and jamb.</li>
<li><strong>Interlocking section joints</strong>, often with their own seals, blocking air between panels.</li>
</ul>
<p>When we see frost lines or daylight around a door, we know the seals have failed regardless of what the core is doing.</p>
<h2>Does glass ruin efficiency?</h2>
<p>Windows in a garage door cost some thermal performance, but you can manage the loss. Insulated double pane glass beats single pane by a wide margin. Frosted or tinted options reduce solar gain. Keeping windows to the top row preserves most of the door\'s insulated area while still letting daylight in. If natural light matters to you, order the door with efficient glass rather than adding it later.</p>
<h2>How does installation quality change the result?</h2>
<p>A high end door installed carelessly performs like a cheap one. The opening must be square, the tracks aligned, and the door balanced so it closes fully and evenly against the seals. Weatherstripping has to be fitted snug to the door face, not just tacked near it. Spring tension must match the door weight so the opener can close the door firmly without straining. These details are the difference between brochure performance and real performance, and they are standard practice on every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">installation we do</a>.</p>
<h2>What habits keep an efficient door efficient?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Keep it closed.</strong> An open door has an R-value of zero. Close it while working in the yard if comfort matters.</li>
<li><strong>Inspect seals yearly.</strong> Rubber hardens and cracks with age and cold. Replace worn seals promptly.</li>
<li><strong>Watch the door\'s behavior.</strong> A door that reverses, hesitates, or sits crooked is not sealing. Mechanical problems have an efficiency cost, so schedule a <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair</a> when something feels off.</li>
<li><strong>Lubricate moving parts.</strong> A smooth, balanced door closes tight and spares the opener.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Is an efficient door worth it if the garage is not heated?</h2>
<p>Usually yes, for three reasons. First, even an unheated garage buffers your home, and a steadier garage means less load on adjacent rooms. Second, the same construction that insulates also strengthens and quiets the door, so you get durability and comfort along with efficiency. Third, if you ever add a workshop, gym, or heater later, the door is already ready for it.</p>
<h2>What should you do next?</h2>
<p>If your current door is a single layer slab, or if you can feel drafts around it, an upgrade will make a difference you can feel from the first cold week. We will measure your opening, walk you through insulation levels and glass options, and install the door so the whole system seals the way it should. <a href="/contact-us/">Contact Twins Garage Doors</a> and we will help you turn the biggest opening in your house into one of its better insulated surfaces.</p>',
4829 => '<p>Insulation is the backbone of a weatherproof garage. It slows heat from escaping in winter and pouring in during summer, keeps condensation in check, and turns the garage from an outdoor space with a roof into a usable buffer zone for your home. Here is how insulation does its job, and where seals and small details fit in.</p>
<h2>Why is the garage the weak point in most homes?</h2>
<p>Builders insulate walls, attics, and windows, but garages often get skipped. The result is a big room bolted to your house that follows the outdoor temperature almost exactly. Every wall it shares with living space becomes a cold wall in January and a hot wall in July. The garage door is the biggest culprit, because it is the largest surface and, on many homes, a thin uninsulated panel.</p>
<h2>How does insulation actually weatherproof a garage?</h2>
<p>Insulation resists heat transfer. Foam in the door and walls creates a thermal buffer, so outdoor temperature swings arrive inside the garage slowly and softened. That does several jobs at once:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Comfort:</strong> the garage stays workable more months of the year.</li>
<li><strong>Protection for what you store:</strong> paint, tools, batteries, and vehicles all do better without extreme swings.</li>
<li><strong>Less strain on the house:</strong> adjacent rooms lose less conditioned air through shared surfaces.</li>
<li><strong>Condensation control:</strong> warmer interior surfaces mean less moisture condensing on the door and walls, which fights rust and mildew.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Where does the garage door fit into the plan?</h2>
<p>Start with the door, because it is the largest opening. An insulated door uses a foam core, either polystyrene panels or injected polyurethane, between steel skins. Polyurethane offers more insulating value per inch and stiffens the door. Better doors also include thermal breaks, which separate the inner and outer steel so heat cannot conduct straight through. If your current door is a single layer slab, upgrading it during a <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> is the single biggest weatherproofing move available for the space.</p>
<h2>Do seals matter as much as insulation?</h2>
<p>Yes. Insulation stops heat moving through surfaces. Seals stop air moving around them. You need both.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bottom seal:</strong> the rubber strip along the door\'s bottom edge conforms to the floor and blocks drafts, water, and pests. It flattens and cracks with age.</li>
<li><strong>Perimeter weatherstripping:</strong> flexible stop molding along the sides and top closes the gap between door and frame.</li>
<li><strong>Threshold seal:</strong> a floor mounted ramp of rubber that helps on uneven slabs where water sneaks under.</li>
<li><strong>Between sections:</strong> quality doors use interlocking joints that limit leakage between panels.</li>
</ul>
<p>A well insulated garage with a daylight gap under the door still feels drafty. When we weatherproof a garage, seals are always part of the checklist, and worn seals are a quick fix on a standard <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair visit</a>.</p>
<h2>What about the rest of the garage?</h2>
<p>Once the door is handled, look at the other surfaces. Insulating the shared walls and the ceiling below any living space pays off next. Weatherstrip the service door like any exterior door. Seal gaps around outlets, hose bibs, and wiring penetrations. If the garage has windows, make sure they close tight. None of these steps are glamorous, but together they finish the envelope the door started.</p>
<h2>Does insulation help in summer too?</h2>
<p>It does. The same foam that holds heat in during winter blocks heat gain in summer. An uninsulated garage with a west facing door can turn brutal by late afternoon, and that heat presses into the house all evening. An insulated door and sealed perimeter keep the space markedly closer to shade temperature, protecting both your comfort and anything sensitive you store out there.</p>
<h2>How do you know if your garage needs attention?</h2>
<ul>
<li>You can see daylight around or under the closed door.</li>
<li>Drafts move across the floor near the door in winter.</li>
<li>The room above or beside the garage always runs cold or hot.</li>
<li>Condensation or frost forms on the inside of the door.</li>
<li>The bottom seal is cracked, stiff, or leaves gaps at the corners.</li>
</ul>
<p>Any of these signs means the space is leaking energy. Some fixes are as small as a new seal. Others call for an insulated door. We are happy to look at the whole picture and tell you honestly which fix gets you the most improvement per dollar. <a href="/contact-us/">Reach out to Twins Garage Doors</a> and we will help you make your garage a weatherproof part of the house instead of a hole in it.</p>',
4830 => '<p>Choose an insulated garage door when the garage is attached to your home, when living space sits above or beside it, when you use the garage as more than parking, or when noise and durability matter to you. Skip it only when a detached shed style garage does nothing but store a mower. That is the short answer. Here is the longer one.</p>
<h2>When does an attached garage demand insulation?</h2>
<p>An attached garage shares walls, and often a ceiling, with your living space. Whatever temperature the garage reaches presses directly on those rooms. In winter an uninsulated door lets the garage drop toward outdoor temperatures, and the house pays for it through every shared surface. In summer the same door lets the garage bake.</p>
<p>An insulated door dampens that swing. The garage becomes a buffer zone instead of an outdoor room, and the bedrooms or kitchen next to it get easier to keep comfortable. For attached garages, we consider insulation the default, not the upgrade.</p>
<h2>What if there is a room above the garage?</h2>
<p>This is the clearest case of all. Bonus rooms and bedrooms over garages are famously the coldest rooms in the house in winter and the warmest in summer. The floor of that room is the garage ceiling, and the garage follows the door. Homeowners who upgrade to a well insulated door consistently tell us the room above finally feels like part of the house. If someone sleeps above your garage, choose insulation and choose a higher R-value while you are at it.</p>
<h2>Do you use the garage as more than parking?</h2>
<p>Think about what actually happens in there.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Workshop:</strong> you cannot do good work in a space that is freezing half the year.</li>
<li><strong>Home gym:</strong> temperature swings make the space unusable exactly when you need the routine most.</li>
<li><strong>Laundry or utility space:</strong> appliances and plumbing prefer moderated temperatures.</li>
<li><strong>Storage:</strong> paint, electronics, batteries, and wood furniture all suffer in extreme heat and cold.</li>
</ul>
<p>If any of those sound like your garage, an insulated door pays you back in usable hours, not just efficiency.</p>
<h2>Does climate settle the question?</h2>
<p>Cold winters make the case strongly. An insulated door keeps the garage warmer, which protects vehicles, reduces frost and condensation, and takes the edge off that morning walk to the car. Hot summers make the same case from the other direction, slowing heat gain so the garage does not become an oven. In a climate with both, the door earns its keep all year. Mild coastal climates are the one place where the value is mostly about the other benefits below.</p>
<h2>What benefits come along beyond temperature?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Quieter operation.</strong> Foam filled sections dampen vibration, so the door runs noticeably quieter. Under a bedroom, this alone justifies the choice.</li>
<li><strong>Strength.</strong> The foam core bonds the skins into a stiffer panel that resists dents from basketballs, bikes, and daily life.</li>
<li><strong>Sound blocking.</strong> Street noise stays out, and workshop noise stays in.</li>
<li><strong>Longevity.</strong> Stiffer sections flex less over thousands of cycles, which is kinder to the whole system.</li>
</ul>
<h2>When is an insulated door not worth it?</h2>
<p>We will be straight with you. A detached garage that only stores lawn equipment, on a tight budget, does not need a premium insulated door. A basic door will protect the space from weather just fine. If the detached garage is your workshop, though, insulation goes right back on the list, because a detached shop relies entirely on its own envelope.</p>
<h2>Should you wait for your current door to fail?</h2>
<p>If your existing door is aging, plan the upgrade on your schedule instead of waiting for a failure that forces a rushed decision. A door that is rusting, sagging, cracking, or constantly needing <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repairs</a> is telling you its timeline. Replacing it deliberately lets you pick the right insulation level, style, and glass instead of taking whatever is available in an emergency.</p>
<h2>How do you pick the right insulated door?</h2>
<p>Match the R-value to the situation: moderate for attached parking garages, higher for garages with living space above or real time spent inside. Choose polyurethane cores for the best performance and quietest operation. Make sure the door includes good perimeter seals and thermal breaks, and have the springs sized for the new weight during <a href="/garage-door-installation/">installation</a>.</p>
<p>Not sure which side of the line your garage falls on? Tell us how you use the space and we will give you an honest recommendation. Call Twins Garage Doors and we will help you decide if now is the time.</p>',
4853 => '<p>Garage door seals are what stand between your garage and every draft, puddle, leaf, and mouse that wants inside. Insulation gets the attention, but the humble rubber around your door does the daily work of keeping the space dry, clean, and comfortable. When seals wear out, the whole garage feels it, and the fix is one of the cheapest in home maintenance.</p>
<h2>What do garage door seals actually do?</h2>
<p>A closed garage door is not naturally tight. Between the door and the floor, the jambs, and the header, there are gaps on all four sides, plus joints between every section. Seals close those gaps. Their jobs include:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Blocking drafts</strong> that make the garage, and the rooms beside it, cold and dirty.</li>
<li><strong>Keeping water out</strong> during rain and snowmelt.</li>
<li><strong>Stopping pests</strong>, because mice need only a tiny gap.</li>
<li><strong>Holding back dust, leaves, and windblown debris.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Protecting your insulation investment</strong>, since air leaks undo what a foam core accomplishes.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What types of seals does a door use?</h2>
<h3>Bottom seal</h3>
<p>The rubber or vinyl strip along the bottom edge of the door, usually held in an aluminum retainer. It compresses against the floor to conform to small dips and cracks. This seal takes the most abuse, sitting in water, salt, and grit, and it is the most common one to fail.</p>
<h3>Threshold seal</h3>
<p>A rubber ramp glued to the floor under the closed door. Thresholds shine on sloped or uneven slabs where water runs toward the garage, giving the bottom seal something flat and raised to land on.</p>
<h3>Side and top weatherstripping</h3>
<p>Flexible vinyl stop molding attached to the jambs and header, with a fin that presses against the face of the door. It blocks drafts and rain at the perimeter and covers the gap that daylight loves to sneak through.</p>
<h3>Between-section seals</h3>
<p>Quality doors use interlocking section joints, and some add gasket material between panels, limiting air leakage through the face of the door itself.</p>
<h2>How do you know your seals have failed?</h2>
<ul>
<li>You can see daylight under or around the closed door.</li>
<li>Leaves, dust, or snow collect inside along the door.</li>
<li>Water lines or puddles appear after rain.</li>
<li>Drafts move across the floor in winter.</li>
<li>The bottom seal looks cracked, flattened, or brittle, or has chunks missing.</li>
<li>Evidence of mice or insects shows up near the door.</li>
</ul>
<p>Rubber does not last forever. Cold makes it stiff, sun makes it brittle, and every cycle of the door compresses it. Most seals give years of service, then fade gradually, which is why homeowners often do not notice until the drafts get bad.</p>
<h2>Why do failed seals cost you money?</h2>
<p>Air leakage is the quiet tax. If your garage is attached, the drafts pouring under the door cool the garage, and the garage cools the rooms around it. Your furnace works harder for the same comfort. If you have paid for an insulated door, worn seals are throwing away part of that investment, because insulation only controls heat moving through the door, not air moving around it. Moisture is the other cost. Water that sneaks in feeds rust on tracks and hardware, mildew on stored goods, and ice patches in winter.</p>
<h2>Can you replace seals yourself?</h2>
<p>Bottom seals slide into a retainer track and are a reasonable project for a handy homeowner, though getting the right profile and size matters, since there are many styles that do not interchange. Perimeter weatherstripping requires careful fitting so the fin presses the door face evenly without dragging. If the door itself sits crooked, no seal will close the gap, because the real problem is balance or alignment, and that calls for a professional <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a>. We replace seals on most service visits, and we always check whether a gap is a seal problem or a door problem first.</p>
<h2>How do you keep seals healthy longer?</h2>
<ul>
<li>Rinse grit and road salt off the bottom seal a few times a year.</li>
<li>Keep the door balanced so it closes evenly and does not crush one side of the seal.</li>
<li>In winter, free a frozen seal gently instead of forcing the opener, which can tear the rubber.</li>
<li>Have seals inspected during routine maintenance visits.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Ready for a draft-free garage?</h2>
<p>If you can see light around your closed door or feel winter coming under it, new seals will make a difference the first cold night. And if you are upgrading the whole door, every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">installation we do</a> includes a complete, properly fitted seal package. Give Twins Garage Doors a call and we will button up your garage.</p>',
4856 => '<p>Weatherstripping cuts garage energy waste by closing the air gaps around your garage door, which are the paths that leak the most heat in winter and let the most hot air in during summer. Insulation slows heat moving through the door. Weatherstripping stops air moving around it. Of the two, worn weatherstripping is the cheaper fix and often the more noticeable one.</p>
<h2>Where does a garage actually lose energy?</h2>
<p>Picture the closed door. There is a gap along the floor, gaps up both sides, a gap across the top, and joints between every section. None of these are sealed by the door alone. Add the service door, windows, and wall penetrations, and a typical garage has a surprising amount of open pathway to the outdoors.</p>
<p>Air moves through those paths constantly. Cold air pushes in low, warm air escapes high, and wind drives the exchange faster. That churn is why an unsealed garage tracks the outdoor temperature so closely no matter what the walls are made of.</p>
<h2>How does weatherstripping stop the loss?</h2>
<p>Each seal targets a specific gap:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bottom seal:</strong> the rubber strip under the door compresses against the floor, closing the largest and leakiest gap.</li>
<li><strong>Side and top weatherstripping:</strong> vinyl stop molding with a flexible fin presses against the door face, sealing the perimeter.</li>
<li><strong>Threshold seal:</strong> a floor mounted ramp that mates with the bottom seal on uneven slabs.</li>
<li><strong>Section joints:</strong> interlocking panel edges limit leakage through the door face.</li>
</ul>
<p>With the paths closed, air exchange slows dramatically. The garage holds a more moderate temperature, and if the garage is attached, the rooms that share its walls stop bleeding conditioned air into a cold buffer.</p>
<h2>Why does this show up on your energy bill?</h2>
<p>Your furnace and air conditioner respond to load. An attached garage that swings with the weather adds load through every shared wall and ceiling. Moderate the garage and you shrink that load. The effect is largest in homes with bedrooms over the garage, ductwork running through it, or frequent door use in cold months. Weatherstripping does not need electricity or maintenance beyond occasional replacement, so the savings, once installed, are passive and continuous.</p>
<h2>How do you know your weatherstripping is wasting energy?</h2>
<ul>
<li>Daylight is visible around the closed door.</li>
<li>You feel a draft along the floor near the door.</li>
<li>Snow, leaves, or dust sift in along the edges.</li>
<li>The rubber is cracked, flattened, stiff, or pulling loose.</li>
<li>The room above the garage runs cold in winter.</li>
</ul>
<p>Rubber and vinyl age with sun, cold, and use. If your seals are original to an older door, assume they are past their best.</p>
<h2>Does quality matter, or is all weatherstripping the same?</h2>
<p>Quality matters more than people expect. Cheap seals harden quickly in cold climates and crack within a few seasons. Better materials stay flexible in deep cold, resist UV, and keep their spring after thousands of compressions. Fit matters just as much. A bottom seal with the wrong profile leaves corner gaps. Perimeter molding nailed too far from the door face seals nothing, and molding pressed too hard drags and wears. We fit seals for a living, and the difference between a snug seal and an almost-seal is the difference between a warm garage and a wind tunnel.</p>
<h2>What if the door itself is the leak?</h2>
<p>Sometimes we get called for drafts and find the weatherstripping is fine, but the door is not closing square. A door that sits crooked, reverses early, or does not compress the bottom seal evenly has a balance or alignment problem. No amount of rubber fixes that. It needs a <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> so the door meets the seals the way it was designed to. This is why we check door operation before replacing seals on a service call.</p>
<h2>What is the best order of upgrades for an inefficient garage?</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Fix the door\'s operation</strong> so it closes fully and evenly.</li>
<li><strong>Replace worn weatherstripping</strong> on all four sides, plus a threshold if the slab is uneven.</li>
<li><strong>Weatherstrip the service door</strong> like any exterior door.</li>
<li><strong>Upgrade to an insulated door</strong> if yours is a single layer slab. A new <a href="/garage-door-installation/">installation</a> includes a fresh, complete seal package.</li>
<li><strong>Insulate shared walls and the ceiling</strong> under any living space.</li>
</ol>
<p>Steps one and two cost the least and often deliver the most immediate comfort.</p>
<h2>Want the drafts gone before the next cold snap?</h2>
<p>We stock quality seal profiles and fit them right the first time, and we will tell you honestly if your gaps are a seal problem or a door problem. Call Twins Garage Doors and stop paying to heat the outdoors.</p>',
4857 => '<p>Choosing the right garage door seals means matching four different seal types to the four different gaps around your door: a bottom seal for the floor, weatherstripping for the sides and top, a threshold for uneven slabs, and sound section joints between panels. Get the profiles and materials right and the garage stays dry, warm, and pest free. Here is how we choose them on the job.</p>
<h2>Why is there no single seal for a garage door?</h2>
<p>Each gap around the door behaves differently. The floor gap deals with standing water, grit, and salt. The side gaps face wind driven rain and sun. The top gap mostly handles drafts. The joints between sections flex thousands of times a year. One material and shape cannot do all of those jobs, which is why a proper seal package uses several parts.</p>
<h2>How do you choose a bottom seal?</h2>
<p>The bottom seal is the strip along the door\'s lowest edge, held in an aluminum or steel retainer. Choosing one comes down to three questions.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>What profile fits your retainer?</strong> Bottom seals come in T shaped, bead, and bulb styles that slide into matching retainer channels. The wrong profile falls out or leaves gaps. If the old retainer is corroded, replace it along with the rubber.</li>
<li><strong>How uneven is your floor?</strong> A larger bulb seal conforms to dips and cracks better than a thin strip. Old slabs usually want the bigger bulb.</li>
<li><strong>What is the material?</strong> Quality rubber and vinyl stay flexible in deep cold. Bargain material stiffens and cracks after a couple of winters, then leaks exactly when you need it most.</li>
</ul>
<h2>When do you need a threshold seal?</h2>
<p>A threshold is a rubber ramp adhered to the floor where the door closes. Choose one when water runs toward the garage, when the slab has settled unevenly, or when wind pushes leaves and dust under the door despite a good bottom seal. The threshold gives the bottom seal a raised, flat surface to land on. One caution: thresholds also hold water in when you hose out the garage, so we recommend them for the specific problems above rather than for every door.</p>
<h2>What should you look for in side and top weatherstripping?</h2>
<p>Perimeter weatherstripping is the stop molding with a flexible fin that presses against the face of the door. The choices that matter:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Flexibility in cold weather.</strong> The fin must keep pressing on the door in January, not freeze into a stiff blade that cracks.</li>
<li><strong>UV resistance.</strong> Sun facing sides age fastest. Better vinyl keeps its color and spring.</li>
<li><strong>Correct placement.</strong> The molding must be installed so the fin compresses lightly and evenly against the door. Too far away and it seals nothing. Too tight and it drags, squeaks, and wears out.</li>
</ul>
<p>Placement is where most do-it-yourself installs fall short. The material is only half the answer. The fit is the other half.</p>
<h2>Do the joints between sections need seals?</h2>
<p>On most residential doors, interlocking section joints handle this, and the design of the door determines how tight they are. Higher quality doors use shiplap or tongue and groove style meeting rails that block airflow when the door is closed. If your door has flat, worn joints that show daylight when closed, no add-on strip fixes that well, and it may be a sign the door is due for replacement. We are glad to assess that during a <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair visit</a>.</p>
<h2>How do seals and door condition work together?</h2>
<p>Seals can only close gaps the door presents evenly. A door that closes crooked crushes the seal on one side and leaves a gap on the other. A door that reverses before fully closing never compresses the bottom seal at all. If you replace seals and still see daylight, the door\'s balance, tracks, or opener settings are the real problem. Sorting that out is standard <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> work, and it should come before or along with new seals.</p>
<h2>What does a complete seal package look like?</h2>
<ol>
<li>Fresh bottom seal in a sound retainer, profile matched, sized for the floor\'s condition.</li>
<li>New side and top weatherstripping, fitted with even, light compression.</li>
<li>A threshold only where the slab or drainage calls for it.</li>
<li>A door that closes square and compresses everything evenly.</li>
</ol>
<p>That combination is what turns a drafty garage into a dry, quiet one. It is also standard on every new <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> we perform.</p>
<h2>Want it sealed right the first time?</h2>
<p>Bring us the drafts, the puddles, or the mouse problem, and we will match the right seals to your door and floor, check that the door closes true, and fit everything snug. Call Twins Garage Doors and seal the deal.</p>',
4858 => '<p>Weatherstripping for a garage door is a system of seals: a bottom seal against the floor, vinyl molding along the sides and top, an optional threshold on the slab, and tight joints between sections. Together they block drafts, water, dust, and pests. Here are the ins and outs of what each piece does, when it wears out, and how to get it right.</p>
<h2>What counts as garage door weatherstripping?</h2>
<p>People often picture only the strip under the door, but the full package covers every edge:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Bottom seal:</strong> a rubber or vinyl strip in a retainer along the door\'s bottom edge. It compresses against the concrete and takes the most abuse of any seal on the door.</li>
<li><strong>Side and top weatherstripping:</strong> flexible stop molding fastened to the jambs and header, with a fin that presses against the door face.</li>
<li><strong>Threshold seal:</strong> a rubber ramp glued to the floor, used when the slab is uneven or water drains toward the garage.</li>
<li><strong>Section seals:</strong> the interlocking joints between door panels, which limit air moving through the face of the door.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What does weatherstripping actually protect you from?</h2>
<h3>Drafts and energy waste</h3>
<p>Air leaks are how garages lose the battle with the weather. Sealing the perimeter slows the constant exchange of inside and outside air, which keeps the garage more moderate and reduces the load on rooms that share walls with it. If you have an insulated door, weatherstripping is what lets the insulation do its job, because foam cannot stop a draft flowing around it.</p>
<h3>Water</h3>
<p>Rain and snowmelt follow the floor right to your door. A healthy bottom seal, helped by a threshold where needed, keeps the water outside instead of pooling under your vehicles and freezing into a skating rink in winter.</p>
<h3>Pests</h3>
<p>Mice squeeze through startlingly small gaps, and insects need less than that. The corner where the bottom seal meets the jamb is a favorite entry point. Fresh, properly sized seals close the door on all of them.</p>
<h3>Dust and debris</h3>
<p>Wind drives grit, leaves, and pollen under and around a poorly sealed door. If you sweep out a pile of debris every week, your weatherstripping is telling you something.</p>
<h2>How long does weatherstripping last?</h2>
<p>It depends on material quality, sun exposure, and climate. Cold stiffens rubber, UV makes vinyl brittle, and every door cycle compresses the bottom seal. Expect years of service from quality material, but not forever. The aging is gradual, which is why most homeowners only notice when drafts, water, or daylight force the issue. A quick look twice a year keeps you ahead of it.</p>
<h2>What are the signs it is time to replace seals?</h2>
<ul>
<li>Daylight visible under or around the closed door.</li>
<li>Cracked, flattened, stiff, or torn rubber, especially at the bottom corners.</li>
<li>Water stains or puddles inside after rain.</li>
<li>Drafts you can feel along the floor.</li>
<li>Debris or snow sifting in along the edges.</li>
<li>Molding that has pulled away from the jamb or lost contact with the door.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Can you install weatherstripping yourself?</h2>
<p>A handy homeowner can replace a bottom seal, provided the profile matches the retainer, and there are many profiles that do not interchange. Perimeter molding is trickier than it looks. The fin has to compress lightly and evenly against the door along its whole length. Nail it a little too far out and it seals nothing. A little too tight and the door drags on it, squeaks, and chews through the vinyl. Cold weather installation is harder still because the material loses flexibility.</p>
<p>The bigger caveat is the door itself. Weatherstripping seals a door that closes square. If your door sits crooked, reverses early, or does not press the floor evenly, the gap is a symptom of a balance or alignment issue. That is <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> territory, and it should be corrected first, or the new seals will fail early on the crushed side and leak on the open side.</p>
<h2>Does weatherstripping quality really vary that much?</h2>
<p>Yes. The difference shows up two winters in. Budget material hardens in the cold, cracks, and stops springing back. Better rubber and vinyl compounds stay flexible in deep cold, shrug off UV, and keep sealing after thousands of compressions. Since labor is the same either way, quality material is the better buy almost every time.</p>
<h2>How does weatherstripping fit into the bigger picture?</h2>
<p>Think of your garage in layers: a door that operates correctly, seals that close the perimeter, insulation that slows heat through the surfaces. Weatherstripping is the middle layer, cheap and high impact. If the door itself is a thin, uninsulated slab, pairing new seals with an insulated <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> finishes the job, and a new door comes with a complete factory fresh seal package.</p>
<p>If your garage fails the daylight test, we can fix that. Call Twins Garage Doors and we will fit the right seals, check the door closes true, and leave your garage dry and draft free.</p>',
4859 => '<p>A thermal break is a strip of non-conductive material placed between the inner and outer steel skins of a garage door. Without it, heat travels straight through the metal, and even a foam filled door leaks energy at every point where steel touches steel. Thermal breaks are the detail that separates doors that insulate on paper from doors that insulate in practice.</p>
<h2>Why does steel need a thermal break?</h2>
<p>Steel is superb at conducting heat. That is fine for a frying pan and a problem for a door. Picture a winter day. The outer skin of the door sits at outdoor temperature. If the inner skin connects to it directly through metal, heat from the garage flows out through those connections like water through an open drain. Engineers call this a thermal bridge.</p>
<p>Foam insulation between the skins handles the broad area of each panel. But at the edges, joints, and end caps, the two skins come close together. A thermal break, usually a tough plastic or rubber separator, interrupts the metal path so heat has no easy highway from inside to outside.</p>
<h2>What happens in a door without thermal breaks?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Cold stripes and condensation.</strong> The interior face of the door develops cold lines along section edges where the bridge exists. Moist garage air condenses there, and in deep cold you can see frost patterns tracing the door\'s frame lines.</li>
<li><strong>Lost efficiency.</strong> The door\'s real world performance falls short of the insulation\'s rating, because heat exits through the bridges instead of fighting through the foam.</li>
<li><strong>Corrosion over time.</strong> Repeated condensation along the same lines feeds rust on hardware and staining on the door back.</li>
</ul>
<p>The frustrating part is that none of this shows up in a showroom. Two doors can look identical and carry similar stickers, while only one has its skins properly separated.</p>
<h2>Where are thermal breaks located in a quality door?</h2>
<p>Look for separation at every point the skins approach each other:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Section edges and meeting rails</strong>, where panels join and interlock.</li>
<li><strong>End caps and stiles</strong> at the sides of each section.</li>
<li><strong>Around glazing</strong>, where window frames pass through the door.</li>
<li><strong>Top and bottom rails</strong>, where retainers and astragals mount.</li>
</ul>
<p>In a well built polyurethane door, the injected foam itself bonds the skins while keeping them apart, and molded breaks finish the edges. The result is a door where the inner skin stays close to garage temperature instead of tracking the weather.</p>
<h2>How do thermal breaks and R-value relate?</h2>
<p>R-value describes resistance to heat flow, and manufacturers often measure it at the center of a panel, the best performing spot on the door. Thermal bridges live at the edges, exactly where that measurement does not look. This is why we tell customers that R-value is a useful comparison number but not the whole story. A door with a moderate rating and well executed thermal breaks can outperform a door with a bigger number and bridged edges. Construction details beat brochure numbers.</p>
<h2>Do thermal breaks matter if your garage is unheated?</h2>
<p>They still help. An unheated attached garage acts as a buffer between your house and the outdoors, and the door largely sets the garage\'s temperature. Better door construction keeps the buffer warmer in winter and cooler in summer, which eases the load on every room that shares a wall or ceiling with the garage. If a bedroom sits above your garage, the quality of the door\'s construction is something that room feels every day.</p>
<h2>What should you ask when shopping for an efficient door?</h2>
<ol>
<li>Is the core polystyrene or injected polyurethane?</li>
<li>Are the skins separated by thermal breaks at the edges and joints, or does steel touch steel?</li>
<li>How do the sections seal against each other when closed?</li>
<li>What does the perimeter seal package include?</li>
</ol>
<p>Any installer worth hiring can answer these in plain language. We walk through them on every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> quote, because the honest answer sometimes changes which door we recommend.</p>
<h2>Can you add thermal breaks to an existing door?</h2>
<p>Not practically. Thermal breaks are built into the door\'s construction, molded into edges and joints at the factory. Retrofit insulation kits can improve a single layer door\'s panel area, but they cannot fix bridged edges. If your current door frosts along its section lines every winter, the durable fix is a better built door. In the meantime, keeping the door sealed and operating correctly protects what performance it has, and our <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair team</a> can help with that.</p>
<p>Thermal breaks are unsung because they are invisible. But if you want a garage that holds its temperature, they belong on your checklist. Call Twins Garage Doors and we will show you doors that are built right where it does not show.</p>',
4860 => '<p>The best weatherstripping material for a garage depends on the job each seal does: durable rubber for the bottom seal that meets the floor, flexible UV resistant vinyl for the side and top molding, and heavy rubber for thresholds. No single material wins everywhere, which is why quality doors use a mix. Here is how the materials compare and where each belongs.</p>
<h2>What jobs does garage weatherstripping have to do?</h2>
<p>Before comparing materials, it helps to name the demands. Garage seals must stay flexible in freezing cold, survive sun exposure without cracking, spring back after thousands of compressions, resist water, road salt, and oil drips, and hold their shape for years. Different spots around the door emphasize different demands, and that is what drives material choice.</p>
<h2>Which materials are used for bottom seals?</h2>
<p>The bottom seal lives the hardest life on the door. It sits in water and grit, gets crushed on every close, and freezes to the slab in winter.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Rubber:</strong> the classic choice. Good rubber compounds stay pliable in the cold and conform well to rough concrete. Quality varies widely, and bargain rubber stiffens and cracks within a few seasons.</li>
<li><strong>Vinyl (PVC):</strong> common and economical. It handles moderate climates well but tends to harden in deep cold faster than good rubber.</li>
<li><strong>TPE and similar modern blends:</strong> engineered thermoplastics that combine rubber-like flexibility with strong weather resistance. Increasingly what better manufacturers ship.</li>
</ul>
<p>Shape matters along with material. Larger bulb and U profiles conform to uneven slabs better than thin strips. The profile also must match your retainer, since T style, bead, and other designs do not interchange.</p>
<h2>What works best for side and top weatherstripping?</h2>
<p>Perimeter molding needs a rigid mounting section plus a soft fin that presses against the door face. Flexible vinyl dominates here for good reason. It machines into that dual firmness shape well, takes paint-friendly finishes, and resists sun. The quality difference shows in the fin: better vinyl fins stay soft and springy through winters, while cheap fins turn to brittle blades that crack and stop sealing. Some products use a vinyl base with a rubber fin to get the best of both.</p>
<h2>When does a threshold seal earn its place?</h2>
<p>Thresholds are heavy rubber ramps glued to the floor where the door closes. Choose thick, dense rubber rated for vehicles driving over it daily. A threshold makes sense when the slab is wavy, when water drains toward the garage, or when wind pushes debris under an otherwise good bottom seal. Skip it if you regularly hose out the garage, because it will hold that water in.</p>
<h2>How do foam and brush seals fit in?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Foam tape:</strong> useful on the garage service door and windows, but too fragile for the main door\'s moving edges. It compresses permanently and tears easily.</li>
<li><strong>Brush seals:</strong> rows of dense bristles, common on commercial and rolling doors. They excel at blocking debris and pests on surfaces that slide rather than press, but they are not an airtight choice for a typical home sectional door.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Does climate change the right answer?</h2>
<p>Cold climates are the acid test. Materials that perform fine in mild weather stiffen just when sealing matters most, and a frozen stiff seal leaks and tears. For homes with real winters, prioritize compounds rated to stay flexible in deep cold for the bottom seal and fin material, and expect to pay a little more for it. The labor to install cheap and good material is identical, so the better compound is almost always the smarter spend.</p>
<h2>What ruins good material anyway?</h2>
<p>Fit and door condition. A premium bottom seal in the wrong profile leaves corner gaps. Perimeter molding mounted too far from the door seals nothing, and mounted too tight it drags and wears out fast. And no material seals a door that closes crooked. If the door is out of balance or the tracks are off, it crushes one end of the seal and floats above the other. That is a mechanical problem, and fixing it is ordinary <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> work that should come before new rubber goes on.</p>
<h2>How do you get the right materials without becoming a seal expert?</h2>
<p>That is our job. We carry proven profiles and compounds, match them to your retainer and slab, and fit them so they compress evenly. If you are replacing the whole door, every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">new door we install</a> arrives with a complete seal package matched to the door. Either way, tell Twins Garage Doors about the drafts, and we will pick the materials that will still be sealing your garage many winters from now.</p>',
4861 => '<p>Your garage door deserves high-quality weatherstripping because the seals are what make every other part of the garage work: they keep heated air in, water and pests out, and they protect the insulation you paid for. Cheap seals fail in a couple of winters. Good ones quietly do their job for years. The price difference is small, and the performance difference is not.</p>
<h2>What is weatherstripping protecting, exactly?</h2>
<p>A garage door only looks like it closes tight. In reality there are gaps at the floor, along both jambs, across the header, and at every joint between sections. Weatherstripping closes them:</p>
<ul>
<li>The <strong>bottom seal</strong> compresses against the concrete.</li>
<li><strong>Side and top molding</strong> presses a flexible fin against the door face.</li>
<li>An optional <strong>threshold</strong> bridges uneven slabs.</li>
<li><strong>Section joints</strong> interlock to limit leaks through the door itself.</li>
</ul>
<p>Everything that matters in your garage sits behind those seals: your vehicles, tools, stored belongings, and the comfort of every room that shares a wall with the space.</p>
<h2>What does cheap weatherstripping actually cost you?</h2>
<h3>Energy</h3>
<p>Failed seals let air pour around the door around the clock. Cold air in winter, hot air in summer. If your garage is attached, that leakage loads your furnace and air conditioner through every shared surface. If you invested in an insulated door, worn seals quietly cancel part of that investment, because insulation cannot stop air flowing around it.</p>
<h3>Water damage</h3>
<p>A hardened bottom seal stops conforming to the floor, and rain and snowmelt find the low spots. Water inside means rust on tracks and hardware, mildew on cardboard and fabric, stains on the slab, and ice patches in winter right where you step out of the car.</p>
<h3>Pests</h3>
<p>Mice need only a tiny gap, and the corners where a shrunken bottom seal meets the jamb are their favorite doorway. Once inside, they find a warm space full of nesting material. New, properly sized seals are the cheapest pest control you can buy.</p>
<h3>Comfort and use of the space</h3>
<p>A drafty garage is a garage you avoid half the year. Good seals are part of what turns the space into a usable workshop, gym, or project area instead of a cold storage box.</p>
<h2>Why does quality vary so much between seals?</h2>
<p>The differences hide in the material compounds. Bargain rubber and vinyl look identical to the good stuff on day one. The gap shows up over seasons:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Cold flexibility.</strong> Quality compounds stay soft and springy in deep cold. Cheap ones stiffen into plastic blades that crack and stop sealing exactly when winter demands the most.</li>
<li><strong>UV resistance.</strong> Sun bakes the exposed molding. Better vinyl holds its flexibility and color for years.</li>
<li><strong>Compression memory.</strong> The bottom seal is crushed on every close. Good material springs back thousands of times. Poor material flattens and stays flat.</li>
</ul>
<p>Since the labor to install either is the same, material quality is the highest leverage choice in the whole job.</p>
<h2>Is installation part of the quality?</h2>
<p>Absolutely. High-quality weatherstripping fitted poorly performs like cheap weatherstripping. The bottom seal profile must match the retainer. The perimeter fin must compress lightly and evenly along its full length, not seal in the middle and gap at the ends. And the door itself must close square. A door that is out of balance crushes one side of the seal and hovers over the other, wearing out new rubber fast while still leaking. When we get called for drafts, we check door operation first, because sometimes the right fix is a <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> and sometimes it is seals, and often it is both.</p>
<h2>How do you know your current seals are failing?</h2>
<ul>
<li>Daylight shows under or around the closed door.</li>
<li>The rubber is cracked, stiff, torn, or flattened.</li>
<li>Drafts move along the floor in winter.</li>
<li>Puddles, stains, leaves, or snow appear inside along the door.</li>
<li>You have seen mice or insect activity near the door edges.</li>
</ul>
<p>Any one of those is your garage asking for attention.</p>
<h2>When should you replace seals versus the whole package?</h2>
<p>If the door operates well and the panels are sound, fresh quality seals restore the garage on their own. If the door is an aging single layer slab with worn section joints, pairing seals with an insulated <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> upgrades the whole envelope at once, and the new door arrives with a complete factory matched seal package.</p>
<p>Your garage door works every day of the year. Give it seals that can keep up. Call Twins Garage Doors and we will fit weatherstripping that is still doing its job winters from now.</p>',
4879 => '<p>The LiftMaster openers we install most are the 84505R belt drive with built-in camera, the 84504R belt drive with battery backup, the 84602 value belt drive, and the 87504-267 wall mount for garages that need the ceiling clear. All four connect to the myQ app, and all four have earned their spot through years of service calls where we see what holds up.</p>
<h2>Why do we install LiftMaster?</h2>
<p>We work on every brand of opener, and that repair experience shapes what we choose to install. LiftMaster\'s professional line is built to be serviced, parts are available, the myQ smart features work reliably, and the motors last. When we put our name on an installation, we want the opener still working quietly years later, and LiftMaster earns that trust more consistently than anything else we handle.</p>
<h2>Which LiftMaster models do we recommend?</h2>
<h3>LiftMaster 84505R: the smart flagship</h3>
<p>The 84505R is a belt drive opener with an integrated camera, so you can see the garage live from the myQ app, with night vision and two-way audio. Add built-in Wi-Fi, alerts when the door opens, a battery backup option, and a quiet DC motor, and it covers the full wish list for a connected home. This is the model for anyone who wants to check on the garage from anywhere, watch deliveries arrive, or keep an eye on kids coming home.</p>
<h3>LiftMaster 84504R: quiet strength with battery backup</h3>
<p>The 84504R gives you the same quiet belt drive and myQ connectivity with a battery backup, so the door still opens during a power outage. Storms have a way of knocking out power exactly when you need to get a vehicle out, and the backup battery removes that worry. For most families, this is the sweet spot of the lineup.</p>
<h3>LiftMaster 84602: the dependable value pick</h3>
<p>The 84602 is the model we suggest when the budget matters more than the extras. It is still a belt drive, still smooth and quiet, still myQ connected so you get smartphone control and alerts. It skips the camera and some premium touches, and for a straightforward garage it is all the opener most homes need.</p>
<h3>LiftMaster 87504-267: the wall mount space saver</h3>
<p>The 87504-267 mounts on the wall beside the door instead of hanging from the ceiling. That frees the overhead for storage racks or a car lift, eliminates rail vibration through the ceiling, and cleans up the look of the garage. It includes battery backup and a remote LED light, and it is our go-to for garages with high ceilings, tall vehicles, or bedrooms above.</p>
<h2>How do you choose between belt drive and wall mount?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Choose a belt drive ceiling model</strong> for typical garages. Belts run quietly, need little maintenance, and cost less than wall mounts.</li>
<li><strong>Choose the wall mount</strong> when ceiling space is precious, the ceiling is high or vaulted, or you want the quietest possible operation under living space.</li>
</ul>
<p>Either way, the opener must be matched to the door. A heavy insulated double door demands appropriate lifting power and correctly tensioned springs. The opener only moves the door; the springs carry the weight. An opener straining against a poorly balanced door wears out early, which is a large share of the <a href="/garage-door-opener-repair/">opener repairs</a> we run.</p>
<h2>What smart features actually matter?</h2>
<p>After thousands of installs, these are the features customers actually use:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Open and close from the app</strong>, including letting in family or service pros while away.</li>
<li><strong>Alerts</strong> when the door opens, closes, or is left open.</li>
<li><strong>Scheduled closing</strong>, so a forgotten door shuts itself at night.</li>
<li><strong>Battery backup</strong>, which turns a power outage into a non-event.</li>
<li><strong>Camera view</strong> on the 84505R, for package deliveries and peace of mind.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Should you replace an aging opener before it dies?</h2>
<p>If your opener predates modern safety reversal standards, lacks rolling code security, or struggles and strains on every cycle, replacement is the safer and often cheaper path than repeated fixes. If the motor is healthy and the problem is a worn part, an honest <a href="/garage-door-opener-repair/">repair</a> is the right call, and we will tell you which side of that line you are on.</p>
<p>Want a specific recommendation for your garage? Tell us about your door, ceiling, and how you use the space, and we will match you to the right LiftMaster. <a href="/contact-us/">Contact Twins Garage Doors</a> and we will get it installed cleanly and set up on your phone before we leave the driveway.</p>',
4902 => '<p>Lubricating a garage door the right way means using a garage door rated lubricant, applying it to the hinges, rollers, springs, and lock parts, and keeping it off the tracks. Done a couple of times a year, this ten minute chore is the single best thing a homeowner can do to keep a door quiet and extend the life of its moving parts.</p>
<h2>Why does lubrication matter so much?</h2>
<p>A garage door is the largest moving object in your home, and it moves on dozens of metal contact points. Every cycle, hinges pivot, rollers spin, and springs wind and unwind. Dry metal on metal grinds, squeals, and wears. Lubricated metal glides. The difference shows up as a quieter door, smoother travel, less strain on the opener, and parts that last years longer. Most of the screeching doors we get called about need nothing more than proper lubrication and a tune-up.</p>
<h2>What lubricant should you use?</h2>
<p>Use a lubricant made for garage doors, typically a lithium based or silicone based spray from the hardware store.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Lithium grease spray:</strong> clings well to hinges and metal rollers, stays put through temperature swings.</li>
<li><strong>Silicone spray:</strong> good for nylon rollers and weather seals, goes on thin and does not gum up.</li>
</ul>
<p>Avoid WD-40 as your lubricant. It is a fine cleaner and water displacer, but it is too thin to lubricate door hardware for long, and it can wash existing grease out and leave parts drier than before. Skip heavy motor oils and thick shop grease too, since they drip and collect grit.</p>
<h2>Which parts get lubricated?</h2>
<p>Work with the door closed and the opener unplugged so nothing moves while your hands are near the hardware.</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Hinges.</strong> Spray each pivot point where the hinge flexes as the door bends around the track curve.</li>
<li><strong>Rollers.</strong> Lubricate the bearings, the part where the roller spins on its stem. Metal rollers with exposed bearings drink it up. For nylon rollers, keep spray off the nylon wheel surface and hit only the bearing, using silicone if the bearings are sealed.</li>
<li><strong>Springs.</strong> A light coat along the torsion springs above the door quiets them and slows rust. Mist, do not soak.</li>
<li><strong>Bearing plates.</strong> The round bearings at the center and ends of the torsion shaft. A quick shot where the shaft passes through.</li>
<li><strong>Lock and armbar.</strong> If your door has a manual lock, lubricate the mechanism and the pivot points.</li>
<li><strong>Opener rail.</strong> For chain or belt openers, check your manual. Many belt drives need nothing, while some chain rails take a thin film of grease on the top of the rail where the trolley slides.</li>
</ol>
<p>Then run the door through a few full cycles to spread everything, and wipe away drips.</p>
<h2>What should you never lubricate?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>The tracks.</strong> Rollers are meant to roll in the tracks, not slide. Grease in the tracks collects dirt into a grinding paste and can make rollers skate. Keep tracks clean and dry, wiping them with a rag if they are dusty.</li>
<li><strong>The nylon surface of rollers</strong> where it contacts the track, for the same reason.</li>
<li><strong>Weather seals with petroleum products.</strong> Petroleum swells and degrades rubber. If a seal sticks in winter, a silicone spray is the safe choice.</li>
</ul>
<h2>How often should you lubricate?</h2>
<p>Twice a year suits most homes, and we like the change of seasons as a reminder: once before winter, once in spring. Cold thickens grease and shrinks parts, so heading into winter with fresh lubrication keeps the door smooth through the worst months. If the door starts squeaking between sessions, it is fine to touch up sooner.</p>
<h2>What noises does lubrication not fix?</h2>
<p>Lubrication cures squeaks and grinding from dry hardware. Other sounds point elsewhere:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Loud bang from the garage:</strong> possibly a broken spring. Stop using the door and call for <a href="/garage-door-spring-repair/">spring repair</a>. Springs are under high tension and are not a homeowner job.</li>
<li><strong>Rattling or jerky travel:</strong> could be loose hardware, a worn roller, or a track issue, worth a professional look.</li>
<li><strong>Straining opener or a door that feels heavy:</strong> a balance problem. The springs are not carrying their share, and running the door that way wears out the opener. That is a call to our <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair team</a>.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Want the full tune-up done for you?</h2>
<p>Our maintenance visits include lubrication of every point above plus a safety inspection, balance test, hardware tightening, and seal check. It is cheap insurance for the hardest working machine on your house. <a href="/contact-us/">Reach out to Twins Garage Doors</a> and we will keep your door running quiet.</p>',
4913 => '<p>Adding windows to your garage door brings in natural light, upgrades curb appeal, and can raise how the whole front of your house reads from the street. The trade-offs are modest losses in insulation and privacy, both of which the right glass handles. Here is what windows do for a garage door and how to choose them well.</p>
<h2>What does natural light change in a garage?</h2>
<p>More than people expect. A windowless garage is a cave that needs the lights on at noon. A top row of windows washes the space in daylight, which makes the garage genuinely usable as a workshop, gym, or project space during the day. You find tools faster, see what you are doing, and burn less electricity on lighting. If you spend any regular time in the garage, daylight is the benefit you will notice every single day.</p>
<h2>How much do windows improve curb appeal?</h2>
<p>The garage door often takes up a third or more of a home\'s street facing facade, so its design carries real weight. Windows break up the large blank panel, add symmetry and character, and let you echo the style of your home\'s other windows. A few directions we install often:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Traditional grille patterns</strong> that match colonial and craftsman style homes.</li>
<li><strong>Clean long panes</strong> for modern and contemporary houses.</li>
<li><strong>Arched or decorative top sections</strong> for carriage house doors.</li>
<li><strong>Frosted or seeded glass</strong> for texture without a clear view inside.</li>
</ul>
<p>Because the door is so visible, this is one of the few upgrades where a modest option change transforms the look of the whole house. You can preview combinations on a photo of your own home with our <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a>.</p>
<h2>Do windows hurt insulation?</h2>
<p>Glass insulates less than a foam filled steel section, so windows cost some thermal performance. You control how much:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Insulated double pane glass</strong> performs far better than single pane and is the right choice for attached or heated garages.</li>
<li><strong>Keeping windows to the top row</strong> preserves most of the door\'s insulated area, and the top of the garage is where light does the most good anyway.</li>
<li><strong>Tinted or frosted options</strong> cut solar gain on sun facing doors.</li>
</ul>
<p>For a detached or unheated garage, standard glass is usually fine. For a garage under a bedroom or used as living space, order the insulated glass and you will keep nearly all the door\'s comfort.</p>
<h2>What about privacy and security?</h2>
<p>Clear glass in the top row sits high enough that passersby see ceiling, not belongings. If the sightlines still bother you, frosted, obscure, or tinted glass admits the daylight while blocking the view entirely. On security, modern garage door windows are tempered or otherwise safety rated, mounted well above easy reach in most designs, and honestly less inviting than the average house window. Choosing obscure glass removes the ability to inventory your garage from the street, which is the practical concern.</p>
<h2>Can you add windows to an existing door?</h2>
<p>Sometimes, and it depends on the door. Some manufacturers offer window sections or inserts that match specific models, and a top section can occasionally be swapped for a glazed one. The swap must respect the door\'s weight and balance, because a heavier or lighter section changes the spring tension the door needs. This is not a guess-and-go project. If the door is older, the honest comparison is often between retrofitting one section and putting that money toward a new door where the windows, insulation, and seals all come matched from the factory. We are glad to look at your door and give you a straight answer, and if a new door wins, our <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> team handles the rest.</p>
<h2>How do you choose windows you will still love in ten years?</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Match the house, not the trend.</strong> Pick grille patterns and shapes that echo your home\'s existing windows.</li>
<li><strong>Put function first.</strong> Choose insulated glass for attached garages and obscure glass where privacy matters.</li>
<li><strong>Keep proportions simple.</strong> A single glazed row almost always looks right. Overdone glass ages quickly.</li>
<li><strong>Coordinate with color.</strong> Window frames and inserts should work with the door color you choose, not fight it.</li>
</ol>
<h2>Ready to brighten the biggest door on your house?</h2>
<p>Windows are one of the most satisfying upgrades we install, because the difference is visible from the street and felt inside the garage the same day. Try a few looks in the <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a>, then <a href="/contact-us/">contact Twins Garage Doors</a>. We will help you pick glass that looks right, insulates right, and fits your budget.</p>',
4914 => '<p>Automatic garage doors win on convenience, security, and everyday practicality, which is why nearly every door we install gets an opener. Manual doors win on lower upfront cost and simplicity, and they still make sense for detached sheds and rarely used bays. Here are the honest pros and cons of each, from a crew that services both.</p>
<h2>What are the advantages of an automatic garage door?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Convenience.</strong> You open and close the door from the car, in the rain, in the dark, with groceries. This sounds small until you live without it in February.</li>
<li><strong>Security.</strong> Modern openers hold the door closed with the trolley mechanism and use rolling code remotes, which change the access code on every use so a captured signal cannot be replayed. Smart models add alerts and remote control from your phone.</li>
<li><strong>Safety features.</strong> Openers made under modern standards include auto-reverse, which stops and reverses the door if it hits an obstruction, and photo eye sensors that stop closure when anything crosses the beam near the floor. A manual door has neither.</li>
<li><strong>Lighting.</strong> The opener lights the garage the moment you arrive, a genuinely useful touch at night.</li>
<li><strong>Consistency.</strong> The opener closes the door fully and evenly every time, which keeps the weather seals compressed the way they should be.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What are the drawbacks of automatic doors?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Upfront cost.</strong> The opener, installation, and accessories add to the project price.</li>
<li><strong>One more machine to maintain.</strong> Openers have motors, gears, belts, and sensors that eventually need service. When something acts up, our <a href="/garage-door-opener-repair/">opener repair</a> team handles it, but it is a system a manual door simply does not have.</li>
<li><strong>Power dependence.</strong> In an outage a basic opener must be operated with the manual release. Models with battery backup remove this concern, and we recommend them for exactly this reason.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What are the advantages of a manual garage door?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Lower cost.</strong> No opener to buy, install, or power.</li>
<li><strong>Simplicity.</strong> Fewer parts means fewer things to service. Springs, rollers, and hinges still need care, but there is no motor, logic board, or sensor set.</li>
<li><strong>No power required.</strong> The door works the same in an outage as on any other day.</li>
<li><strong>Fine for light duty.</strong> A detached shed you enter a few times a month does not need automation.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What are the drawbacks of a manual door?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Physical effort, every time.</strong> A properly balanced door lifts with modest effort, but you still get out of the car in the weather to do it. If the springs weaken, the door gets heavy fast.</li>
<li><strong>No modern safety systems.</strong> There is no auto-reverse and no photo eye protection for kids and pets. The door is only as safe as the person operating it.</li>
<li><strong>Security depends on habits.</strong> A manual door is only locked if someone locks it. There are no alerts, no remote check, no scheduled closing.</li>
<li><strong>Inconsistent closing.</strong> Doors left slightly open or unevenly closed leak air and invite pests.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Which one is right for your situation?</h2>
<p><strong>Choose automatic</strong> for any attached garage you use daily. The convenience, safety systems, and security features earn their cost many times over, and options like battery backup and smart control cover the traditional weak points. Households with kids, pets, or family members who should not be hauling a heavy door up by hand benefit the most.</p>
<p><strong>Choose manual</strong> for a detached shed, a barn, or a rarely used bay where the budget is better spent elsewhere. Keep the door balanced and the lock in use, and it will serve fine.</p>
<h2>Can you convert a manual door to automatic?</h2>
<p>Usually, yes. Most sectional doors in good condition can have an opener added. The prerequisites are a door that is structurally sound, springs that balance the door correctly, and enough ceiling or wall space for the opener. We check all three before installing, because an opener bolted to an unbalanced door will strain, wear early, and mask a mechanical problem instead of fixing it. If your manual door already feels heavy, that is a spring issue worth addressing first, and our <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair team</a> can sort it during the same visit.</p>
<h2>Want help deciding?</h2>
<p>Tell us how you use the space and we will give you a straight recommendation, whether that is a full <a href="/garage-door-installation/">new door and opener</a> or simply adding automation to the door you have. Call Twins Garage Doors and we will make either path easy.</p>',
4915 => '<p>The top five reasons to insulate your garage door: it moderates the garage\'s temperature, it lowers the load on your home\'s heating and cooling, it quiets the door and the room, it strengthens the door itself, and it protects everything you store inside. If your garage is attached to the house, every one of these applies to you. Here is each reason in plain terms.</p>
<h2>1. Why does temperature control top the list?</h2>
<p>An uninsulated garage door is a thin metal sheet between your garage and the weather. In winter the garage plunges toward outdoor temperatures, and in summer it bakes. An insulated door, with a foam core of polystyrene or polyurethane, slows that heat transfer dramatically. The garage holds a steadier, more moderate temperature all year.</p>
<p>That matters most for attached garages, because the garage acts as a buffer for the rooms around it. It matters doubly for a bedroom over the garage, the room that is famously cold in winter and hot in summer. Homeowners who upgrade tell us that room finally joins the rest of the house.</p>
<h2>2. How does an insulated door reduce energy waste?</h2>
<p>Your furnace and air conditioner fight whatever conditions surround your living space. An attached garage that swings with the seasons presses on the house through every shared wall and ceiling, and your HVAC pays for it. Moderating the garage shrinks that load, so the equipment runs less to keep the same comfort. The door does this passively, every hour, with no power or maintenance. Pair it with healthy weatherstripping, since insulation stops heat moving through the door while seals stop air moving around it, and the two together are what make the garage efficient.</p>
<h2>3. What does insulation do for noise?</h2>
<p>Two things. First, the door itself runs quieter. The foam core bonds the steel skins into a stiff panel that does not rattle, flex, and boom the way a hollow door does. If the door sits under a bedroom, the difference between a hollow door slamming at dawn and an insulated door gliding shut is the difference between waking the house and not.</p>
<p>Second, the door blocks sound crossing it. Street noise stays out of the garage, and workshop noise stays in. If you run power tools, band practice, or a treadmill out there, the neighbors will appreciate the upgrade as much as you do.</p>
<h2>4. Does insulation really make the door stronger?</h2>
<p>Yes, and this is the most overlooked reason on the list. In a foam filled door, especially one with injected polyurethane, the core bonds to both skins and turns each section into a rigid sandwich panel. That structure resists dents from basketballs and bike handles, resists flexing in wind, and holds its shape over thousands of open close cycles. Stiffer sections are also kinder to hinges, rollers, and the opener, because the door tracks straight instead of wobbling. A stronger door simply lasts longer, which protects the money you spent on it.</p>
<h2>5. What does an insulated door protect inside the garage?</h2>
<p>Think about what actually lives in your garage:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Vehicles.</strong> Batteries, fluids, and finishes all prefer moderate temperatures to hard freezes and oven heat.</li>
<li><strong>Tools and equipment.</strong> Temperature swings drive condensation, and condensation drives rust.</li>
<li><strong>Stored belongings.</strong> Paint, adhesives, electronics, photos, and wood furniture degrade in extremes.</li>
<li><strong>The usable space itself.</strong> A moderated garage is a workshop, gym, or hobby room for many more weeks of the year instead of a space you avoid.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Is an insulated door worth it for every garage?</h2>
<p>Almost every attached garage, yes. For a detached garage used only to store a mower, a basic door is fine and we will tell you so. But if the garage touches your living space, if anyone sleeps above it, or if you spend real time out there, insulation is the default choice, not the luxury one. The gains in comfort, quiet, durability, and efficiency arrive together in a single upgrade.</p>
<h2>What is the next step?</h2>
<p>If your current door is a single layer slab, replacing it with an insulated model is a one day project with benefits you feel the first cold week. We will help you pick the right core material and R-value for how you use the garage, and every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> we do includes a full seal package so the insulation can do its job. You can even preview styles on a photo of your home with our <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a>. <a href="/contact-us/">Reach out to Twins Garage Doors</a> and let\'s make your garage the comfortable part of the house it should be.</p>',
4924 => '<p>Garage door springs should be replaced by a trained professional, not as a do-it-yourself project. The springs are wound under extreme tension, they store enough energy to lift a door that weighs as much as a refrigerator, and mistakes with them cause serious injuries every year. Here is how professional replacement works, how to know your springs are done, and what you can safely do yourself.</p>
<h2>Why are springs dangerous to replace yourself?</h2>
<p>The springs are the muscle of the system. The opener only guides the door; the springs carry nearly all of its weight. To do that, torsion springs above the door are wound tight around a steel shaft, holding that energy constantly, even while the door sits still.</p>
<p>Releasing or adding that tension safely requires the correct winding bars, sound anchor hardware, and practiced technique. If tension gets away from someone mid-job, the bar, the spring, or the cone can move violently with no warning. Online videos make the job look routine. Emergency rooms see how it goes wrong. This is the one garage repair where we draw a hard line: leave it to a pro. The same goes for the lift cables, which are under the same tension.</p>
<h2>How do you know a spring is broken?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>You heard a loud bang</strong> from the garage. A breaking torsion spring sounds like something heavy hit the floor.</li>
<li><strong>The door will not open</strong>, or the opener strains and lifts it a few inches before stopping.</li>
<li><strong>A visible gap</strong> appears in the torsion spring above the door, where the coil separated.</li>
<li><strong>The door feels extremely heavy</strong> if you try to lift it by hand.</li>
<li><strong>The door slams closed</strong> or falls faster than normal.</li>
<li><strong>Crooked movement or slack cables</strong>, since a failed spring throws the whole system out of balance.</li>
</ul>
<p>If any of these sound familiar, stop using the door, including the opener. Forcing a door with a broken spring can burn out the opener motor and can drop the door unexpectedly. Keep people, pets, and cars clear and call for <a href="/garage-door-spring-repair/">spring repair</a>. If the door is stuck with your car trapped inside, our <a href="/emergency-garage-services/">emergency service</a> exists for exactly this.</p>
<h2>What does professional spring replacement involve?</h2>
<p>When we replace springs, the visit follows a consistent shape:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Measure and identify.</strong> Springs are matched to the door\'s exact weight, height, and track setup. We measure the old springs\' wire size, diameter, and length, and weigh the door where needed, because the correct spring is a calculation, not a guess.</li>
<li><strong>Secure the door and remove tension safely</strong> using proper winding bars and technique.</li>
<li><strong>Replace in pairs when appropriate.</strong> On two spring doors, both springs have the same mileage. When one breaks, its partner is usually close behind, and replacing both saves a second failure and a second service call.</li>
<li><strong>Inspect the rest of the system.</strong> Cables, bearings, rollers, and hinges live under the same loads. We check them while the system is apart.</li>
<li><strong>Wind, balance, and test.</strong> The door should hover in place when lifted halfway, travel smoothly, and close fully. We also retest the opener\'s safety reversal once the door is balanced.</li>
</ol>
<h2>How long do springs last, and can you extend their life?</h2>
<p>Springs are rated in cycles, one cycle being a full open and close, so their lifespan depends on how much the door gets used. A busy household that cycles the door many times a day uses up springs faster than one that leaves for work once each morning. You can extend spring life in two honest ways: keep the springs lightly lubricated so corrosion does not create weak points, and keep the door balanced and maintained so the springs work as designed. High cycle springs are also available, and they are a smart upgrade for heavily used doors.</p>
<h2>What can you safely do yourself?</h2>
<p>Plenty, just not the springs and cables. Homeowners can lubricate hinges, rollers, and springs with garage door lubricant, keep tracks clean, watch and listen for changes, and test the door\'s balance by pulling the opener\'s release and lifting the door halfway. If it will not stay put, the springs need attention. Report what you noticed and let a technician take it from there. General wear items are also covered on a routine <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> or maintenance visit.</p>
<h2>Broken spring right now?</h2>
<p>We stock the common sizes, replace springs properly matched to your door, and leave the system balanced and tested. Call Twins Garage Doors, and do not wrestle that door in the meantime.</p>',
4970 => '<p>An uneven garage door usually comes from one of four causes: debris in the tracks, loose track hardware, worn rollers, or a problem in the cables and springs. You can safely diagnose all four yourself, and fix the first two. The moment the cause traces to cables or springs, stop, because those parts are under high tension and are strictly professional territory.</p>
<h2>How do you confirm the door is actually uneven?</h2>
<p>Close the door and look at the bottom edge against the floor. A gap at one corner is the clearest sign. Then watch the door run through a full cycle from inside the garage. Signs to note:</p>
<ul>
<li>One side leads the other as the door travels.</li>
<li>The door shudders, hesitates, or scrapes at the same spot every time.</li>
<li>Gaps at the top corners when closed, or a tilted look in the opening.</li>
<li>Grinding or rubbing noises from one side only.</li>
</ul>
<p>Take note of which side sits low or lags. That detail points at the cause.</p>
<h2>Which checks are safe to do yourself?</h2>
<p>Unplug the opener first so nothing moves while you are close to the hardware. Leave the door closed for most of these checks, since a closed door has the least stored energy in the system.</p>
<h3>1. Check the tracks for debris</h3>
<p>Look up and down both vertical tracks and the curved sections. Leaves, pebbles, cobwebs, a lost ball, or packed grime can all crowd a roller and shove one side of the door out of step. Wipe the tracks clean with a rag. Do not grease the tracks. Rollers are meant to roll in clean, dry track, and lubricant in there collects grit into a grinding paste.</p>
<h3>2. Check for loose track hardware</h3>
<p>Tracks are held to the wall and ceiling by brackets. Years of vibration can loosen the fasteners, letting a track lean or wander so the door no longer runs parallel. Look for brackets that shift when you press on them, and snug up visibly loose bolts with a wrench. Tighten only what is loose. Do not unbolt or reposition the tracks themselves, because track alignment sets how the door carries its weight, and moving a track wrong can bind the door or drop it off its rollers.</p>
<h3>3. Look at the rollers</h3>
<p>With the door closed, examine each roller. Worn, cracked, chipped, or wobbling rollers make one side drag behind the other. You can see the problem yourself, but leave replacement to a technician. Several rollers, especially the bottom ones, sit in brackets connected to cables under tension.</p>
<h3>4. Inspect, do not touch, the cables and springs</h3>
<p>Look at the lift cables running up each side of the door and the springs above it. Warning signs include a cable that is frayed, slack, or off its drum, a visible gap in a spring coil, or one side of the door hanging lower with a loose cable on the same side. If you see any of these, the diagnosis is done. Do not adjust, unwind, rehang, or test anything in the counterbalance system. Those parts hold the door\'s full weight, and this is where do-it-yourself repairs cause real injuries.</p>
<h2>Why does an uneven door get worse if you wait?</h2>
<p>An uneven door loads its hardware unevenly. The low side\'s roller stems, hinges, and cable take extra strain, the opener works harder against the bind, and the wear accelerates. What starts as a cosmetic tilt can end as a jammed door, a burned out opener, or a cable failure that drops one side. Uneven operation is also a sealing problem, since a tilted door cannot compress its weatherstripping evenly, so you get drafts as a bonus. Cheap fix early, expensive fix late.</p>
<h2>When should you call a professional?</h2>
<ul>
<li>Cleaning the tracks and snugging loose brackets did not level the door.</li>
<li>Anything in the cables or springs looks frayed, slack, gapped, or off track.</li>
<li>The door feels unusually heavy, will not stay put when lifted halfway, or slams shut.</li>
<li>The door has jumped its tracks or is jammed at an angle.</li>
</ul>
<p>Those symptoms mean the counterbalance system needs professional hands. Our <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> team levels doors, replaces rollers and cables, and rebalances the system routinely, and if a spring is the culprit we handle <a href="/garage-door-spring-repair/">spring repair</a> on the same visit. A door stuck half open with the car inside is what our <a href="/emergency-garage-services/">emergency service</a> is for.</p>
<p>Do the safe checks, pocket the easy wins, and hand off the tension work. Call Twins Garage Doors and we will get your door running level and quiet again.</p>',
4972 => '<p>Photo-cell beams, the small sensors near the floor on both sides of your garage door, are the most important safety device on the whole system. They project an invisible infrared beam across the opening, and if anything breaks that beam while the door is closing, the door stops and reverses. That one function protects children, pets, and vehicles every single day.</p>
<h2>How do photo-cell beams work?</h2>
<p>The system uses two small units mounted on the door tracks a few inches above the floor. One unit sends an infrared beam across the width of the opening, and the other receives it. As long as the receiver sees the beam, the opener is allowed to close the door. The instant anything interrupts the beam, a child chasing a ball, a pet, a bike tire, a trash can, the opener halts the closing door and runs it back open.</p>
<p>The sensors sit low on purpose. That height catches small children and animals, the very things least able to get out of the way and least visible from the driver\'s seat.</p>
<h2>Why do the beams exist at all?</h2>
<p>A closing garage door is heavy, powered, and often operated by someone who cannot see the opening, whether from the car, from inside the house, or from a phone. Before modern safety standards, doors relied only on contact reversal, meaning the door had to actually strike something before reversing, and older units sometimes failed to reverse at all. The results were tragic often enough that the industry changed. Since 1993, federal safety requirements have mandated that residential garage door openers include an entrapment protection system such as photo eyes. If your opener predates that era or is missing its sensors, it lacks the single most effective safeguard the industry has developed, and replacing it should move to the top of the list. Our <a href="/garage-door-opener-repair/">opener team</a> can tell you quickly whether your unit is up to modern standards.</p>
<h2>What happens when photo eyes act up?</h2>
<p>The most common symptom is a door that refuses to close, or starts closing and immediately reverses, often with the opener lights flashing. That behavior is the opener doing its job: it cannot confirm the opening is clear, so it will not close. Usual culprits:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Misalignment.</strong> The two sensors must point precisely at each other. A bump from a broom, bike, or trash can knocks one askew.</li>
<li><strong>Dirty lenses.</strong> Dust, cobwebs, and road grime cloud the lens until the receiver loses the beam.</li>
<li><strong>Sunlight interference.</strong> Low, direct sun can overwhelm a receiver at certain times of day.</li>
<li><strong>Wiring damage.</strong> Stapled or pinched wires along the wall fail with age and vibration.</li>
<li><strong>Obstructions.</strong> Sometimes the beam is honestly blocked by a shovel, a cord, or a leaf pile.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Which fixes can you do yourself?</h2>
<p>Three safe ones. Clear anything sitting in the beam path. Wipe both lenses gently with a soft cloth. And check alignment, since most sensors have an indicator light that glows steady when the units see each other, so you can nudge a bracket gently until the light holds. If the lights still will not settle, or the wiring looks damaged, have it repaired properly rather than living with workarounds.</p>
<h2>Why should you never bypass the sensors?</h2>
<p>We occasionally find sensors unplugged, taped together, or pointed at each other on the same wall so the door will close without protection. We understand the frustration that leads there, and we will still say it plainly: do not do this. A bypassed sensor set removes the layer of protection that exists specifically for kids and pets, and it usually hides a fault that would take one service visit to fix correctly. Holding the wall button to force a close past a fault is designed as a deliberate, attended action, not a lifestyle. If your door needs tricks to close, it needs a <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair</a>.</p>
<h2>How do you test the safety systems?</h2>
<p>Once in a while, run two quick checks. First, start the door closing and wave an object like a broom handle through the beam near the floor. The door should reverse immediately. Second, test contact reversal by laying a solid object such as a board flat under the door\'s path; the door should reverse when it touches. If either test fails, stop using the door until it is serviced. These are the same checks we run on every maintenance visit.</p>
<h2>Want the whole system checked?</h2>
<p>Photo eyes, reversal force, balance, and hardware all get verified in a standard tune-up. If your sensors are flaky, your opener is from another era, or the door needs coaxing to close, <a href="/contact-us/">contact Twins Garage Doors</a>. We will make the safest device on your house work the way it was designed to.</p>',
4973 => '<p>LiftMaster\'s last three decades track the whole arc of garage door technology: from remotes programmed by tiny switches, to rolling code security, to the myQ app era where a door reports to your phone and answers to voice assistants. The garage door opener went from a dumb motor to a connected device, and LiftMaster drove much of that change.</p>
<h2>Where did it start: what were switch-based remotes?</h2>
<p>Early garage remotes used small DIP switches, rows of tiny toggles inside the remote and the opener. You set both to the same pattern, and that pattern was your code, fixed until someone changed the switches by hand. It worked, but it had two problems. The number of combinations was limited, and the code never changed. Anyone with a scanner, or a matching remote and patience, could stumble onto your pattern. In an era when garages increasingly connected directly to houses, that was a real security gap.</p>
<h2>How did rolling code change garage security?</h2>
<p>The breakthrough was rolling code technology, introduced under the Security+ name in the 1990s. Instead of one fixed code, the remote and opener share an algorithm that generates a new code on every single press. A captured signal is useless because that code has already expired. This closed the door on code grabbing and replay attacks, and it remains the foundation of garage door security today. It is also why we tell homeowners with pre-rolling-code openers that an upgrade is a security decision, not just a convenience one.</p>
<h2>When did the garage door join the smart home?</h2>
<p>The next leap was connectivity. LiftMaster\'s myQ technology, which debuted in 2013, put the opener on your home network and the controls on your phone. That unlocked things a wall button never could:</p>
<ul>
<li>Open or close the door from anywhere, and check whether you actually closed it.</li>
<li>Alerts when the door opens, closes, or has been left open.</li>
<li>Scheduled closing, so a forgotten door shuts itself at night.</li>
<li>Access sharing for family and trusted visitors without handing out remotes.</li>
</ul>
<p>Follow-on hardware kept pace: battery backup so the door works during outages, integrated LED lighting, automatic deadbolt-style locks, and eventually openers with built-in cameras so the app shows live video of the garage.</p>
<h2>How do Siri, Alexa, and delivery services fit in?</h2>
<p>Once the opener was connected, partnerships multiplied. Integration with Apple\'s ecosystem brought voice control, so asking Siri to close the garage became an ordinary sentence. Amazon\'s Key service uses myQ to allow secure in-garage package delivery, with the door opening for a verified courier and the event logged and watchable. The garage quietly became a delivery room, a monitored entry point, and a node in whatever smart home platform a family already uses.</p>
<h2>What does thirty years of evolution mean for your home?</h2>
<p>It means the age of your opener matters more than people think. The spread between an early unit and a current one is not comfort trim, it is generational:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Security:</strong> fixed codes versus rolling codes and encrypted signals.</li>
<li><strong>Safety:</strong> modern openers pair with photo eye sensors and refined auto-reverse systems.</li>
<li><strong>Resilience:</strong> battery backup keeps the door working through outages.</li>
<li><strong>Awareness:</strong> the door can now tell you its status instead of leaving you wondering at the airport.</li>
</ul>
<p>If your opener still uses DIP switches, it is a museum piece guarding your biggest entry point. Even openers from the early smart era lack features that are now standard.</p>
<h2>Should you upgrade, and to what?</h2>
<p>Our honest rule: if the opener predates rolling code, replace it for security alone. If it strains, stutters, or needs frequent fixes, weigh the repair cost against a modern unit, and our <a href="/garage-door-opener-repair/">opener repair</a> team will give you a straight answer on which side wins. If you are upgrading, pick the features by how you live: battery backup for storm-prone power, a built-in camera if you want eyes on deliveries, a wall mount unit if you need the ceiling clear. We install current LiftMaster models and set up the app before we leave.</p>
<p>Thirty years took the garage door from switches to Siri. Wherever your opener sits on that timeline, <a href="/contact-us/">reach out to Twins Garage Doors</a> and we will bring your garage up to the present day.</p>',
4974 => '<p>Protecting your home from garage remote theft comes down to a few habits: never leave a remote visible in a parked car, switch to a keychain remote or keypad, use your opener\'s lock features, and upgrade any opener that predates rolling code security. Thieves know the garage remote is often the easiest key to a house, and the fixes cost little or nothing.</p>
<h2>Why do thieves target garage remotes?</h2>
<p>Think about what a garage remote actually is: a key to the largest door on your home. In many houses the garage connects directly to the interior, and the door between them is unlocked because the family treats the garage as inside space. A thief who takes a remote from your car does not need to pick a lock or break a window. They press a button, walk in, and close the door behind them, hidden from the street while they work.</p>
<p>The classic version of this crime is simple: a car parked in the driveway or on the street with a remote clipped to the visor, a quick window smash or an unlocked door, and the thief now holds access to your garage, often with your address available from the registration in the glovebox.</p>
<h2>What habits shut this down immediately?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Take the remote out of the parked car.</strong> Especially overnight, especially in the driveway, and always when parking away from home. Treat the remote like a house key, because that is what it is.</li>
<li><strong>Switch to a keychain mini remote.</strong> Small remotes live on your key ring and leave with you every time. The visor clip is the habit to break.</li>
<li><strong>Use the vehicle\'s built-in buttons.</strong> Systems like HomeLink program the opener into the car itself. There is no loose remote to steal, and the car\'s own locks and security protect access.</li>
<li><strong>Lock the door between garage and house.</strong> It is the cheapest second layer you own. If someone does get the garage open, they should meet a locked door, not an open hallway.</li>
<li><strong>Do not leave the registration showing your address with an unattended remote.</strong> The pairing of address plus access is exactly what a thief wants.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What features on your opener help?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Rolling code security.</strong> Modern openers change the access code on every press, so a captured signal cannot be replayed. If your opener is old enough to use fixed codes or DIP switches, this alone justifies replacement, and our <a href="/garage-door-opener-repair/">opener team</a> can confirm what generation you own.</li>
<li><strong>Lock or vacation mode.</strong> Many openers can ignore all remotes while you are away, responding only to the wall console. Use it for trips.</li>
<li><strong>Wireless keypads.</strong> A keypad on the door frame opens the garage with a code, no remote required. Great for kids after school and for eliminating spare remotes floating around.</li>
<li><strong>Smart openers with alerts.</strong> App connected openers notify you the moment the door opens, let you check its status from anywhere, and close it remotely. If a stolen remote is ever used, you know in real time instead of days later.</li>
<li><strong>Automatic closing.</strong> Scheduled or timed closing fixes the other big vulnerability, the door left standing open.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What should you do if a remote is lost or stolen?</h2>
<p>Act the same day. Every opener can be reset so that old remotes stop working, usually by clearing the opener\'s memory and re-pairing only the remotes you still hold. Reprogram your keypad code at the same time. Then, for a while, use the opener\'s lock mode at night and keep the interior door locked. If you are not comfortable doing the reset, we handle it as a quick service call, and it is a standard part of any <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> visit if we are already there.</p>
<h2>Does the rest of the door matter for security?</h2>
<p>Yes. A remote is one path in, but the door system has others worth checking. The emergency release cord should not be reachable or fishable from outside. Windows in the door can be frosted so the garage\'s contents are not on display. The service door deserves a deadbolt like any exterior door. And a door that does not close fully, or reverses before sealing, is effectively unlocked all night, which makes a mechanical problem a security problem too.</p>
<h2>Want your garage checked over?</h2>
<p>We can look at your opener\'s security generation, set up lock modes and keypads, program keychain remotes, and fix anything that keeps the door from closing tight. If an opener upgrade makes sense, we will say so plainly and install a current model with rolling code, app alerts, and automatic closing. <a href="/contact-us/">Contact Twins Garage Doors</a> and make the easiest key to your house a hard one to steal.</p>',
5034 => '<p>A new garage door changes the look of a house more than almost any single upgrade, because on many homes the door covers a third or more of the street facing facade. Swap a faded builder-grade slab for a door with real style, color, and windows, and the whole house reads newer, sharper, and more cared for. Here is how to use that big canvas well.</p>
<h2>Why does the garage door matter so much to curb appeal?</h2>
<p>Stand across the street from your house and look at it honestly. The garage door is likely the largest uninterrupted surface facing the road, bigger than the front door, bigger than any window. Yet most homes wear a plain, aging door chosen by a builder decades ago. That mismatch is why replacing the door is so satisfying: you are redesigning the biggest element in the picture. Real estate pros consistently rank garage door replacement among the improvements that return the most value at resale, precisely because buyers see it before anything else.</p>
<h2>Which door styles change the look the most?</h2>
<h3>Carriage house doors</h3>
<p>These evoke the swing-out doors of old carriage barns, with decorative handles, strap hinges, and paneled or crossbuck designs, while operating as normal sectional doors. On craftsman, farmhouse, and traditional homes they add instant character.</p>
<h3>Modern and contemporary doors</h3>
<p>Clean flush panels, crisp horizontal lines, or full view aluminum and glass doors suit newer architecture. A glass paneled door can turn the garage into a design feature, especially lit from inside at dusk.</p>
<h3>Classic raised panel doors, done well</h3>
<p>Even the familiar raised panel style transforms when you choose a rich color, upgraded texture, and a row of windows. This is the budget-friendly path to a big visual step up.</p>
<h3>Faux wood doors</h3>
<p>Molded and composite finishes now mimic stained wood convincingly, giving you the warmth of a wood door over an insulated steel core, without the refinishing schedule real wood demands.</p>
<h2>How do color and windows sharpen the design?</h2>
<p><strong>Color:</strong> matching the door to the house\'s trim or siding makes the home look composed and intentional. A contrasting door, done deliberately, makes the entry area pop. What ages a house is the faded default white or almond slab that matches nothing.</p>
<p><strong>Windows:</strong> a top row of glass breaks up the panel, echoes the home\'s other windows, and pours daylight into the garage. Grille patterns can match colonial or craftsman details, long clear panes suit modern homes, and frosted glass adds light while keeping privacy.</p>
<p><strong>Hardware:</strong> handles and hinge accents dress carriage styles, while modern designs look best bare. Small choices, visible from the street.</p>
<p>The easiest way to get this right is to see it before you buy. Our <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a> lets you preview styles, colors, and window options on a photo of your own home, which settles most family debates in about ten minutes.</p>
<h2>Can a stylish door still be practical?</h2>
<p>Yes, and it should be. The good news is that the style layer and the performance layer are separate choices on the same door:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Insulation:</strong> foam filled sections keep the garage moderate, run quieter, and stiffen the door against dents. If the garage is attached or has a room above, insulation belongs in the order.</li>
<li><strong>Durable finishes:</strong> factory baked paint and textured steel hold their look for years without repainting.</li>
<li><strong>Fresh seals and hardware:</strong> a new door arrives with a complete seal package, new springs sized to its weight, and quiet rollers, so the upgrade feels as good as it looks.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What does the replacement process look like?</h2>
<p>Simpler than most homeowners expect. We measure the opening, help you finalize style, color, glass, and insulation, and order the door. Installation is typically a single day: the old door and hardware come out, the new door, tracks, and springs go in, seals are fitted, and the opener is tuned to the new door\'s weight and travel. You leave in the morning with the old house and come home to a new one. The full scope is handled by our <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> team, including hauling away the old door.</p>
<h2>Ready to see your house with a better door?</h2>
<p>Play with a few looks in the <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a>, or send us a photo of your home and tell us the style you are after. We will bring samples, honest opinions, and a clean installation. <a href="/contact-us/">Reach out to Twins Garage Doors</a> and give your house the upgrade the whole street will notice.</p>',
5040 => '<p>Twins Garage Doors has earned Superpro status from Housecall Pro, a certification that recognizes home service companies for consistently excellent, modern, and transparent customer service. We are proud of it, and we want to explain in plain terms what the badge means, what it took to earn, and why it matters when you are choosing who works on your home.</p>
<h2>What is the Superpro program?</h2>
<p>Housecall Pro is the platform many home service companies use to run scheduling, dispatch, invoicing, and payments. Its Superpro program sets a bar for how a local service company should operate, and awards the designation only to companies that meet it. The program\'s focus is not marketing polish. It is the day-to-day experience customers actually have: showing up when promised, communicating clearly, making booking and payment easy, and maintaining a track record of highly rated work.</p>
<h2>What did Twins Garage Doors have to meet to earn it?</h2>
<p>Superpro status has concrete eligibility requirements. As of our last update, earning it meant:</p>
<ul>
<li>Maintaining a 4.8 star or higher customer rating.</li>
<li>Offering online booking, so customers can schedule without phone tag.</li>
<li>Accepting modern payment methods, including credit cards, with clean digital invoices.</li>
<li>Keeping an active Google Business Profile and social media presence, so our reviews and information are public and current.</li>
<li>Running the business on professional tools for scheduling, dispatch, and communication.</li>
<li>Agreeing to the Superpro code of ethics and its commitments to customers.</li>
</ul>
<p>None of those are one-time hoops. The rating requirement in particular is earned one job at a time, which is why we treat every spring replacement and every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">door installation</a> as a review in waiting.</p>
<h2>What does this mean for you as a customer?</h2>
<p>Certifications only matter if they change your experience. Here is what the standards behind this one look like from your side of the driveway:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Easy scheduling.</strong> Book online or call, your choice, with real appointment windows.</li>
<li><strong>Clear communication.</strong> You know who is coming and when, and you hear from us if anything changes.</li>
<li><strong>Transparent pricing.</strong> Estimates and invoices are written, itemized, and digital. No mystery math on a clipboard.</li>
<li><strong>Modern payment.</strong> Pay by card or other current methods and get your receipt instantly.</li>
<li><strong>Accountability.</strong> Our rating is public and fragile by design. Every review, good or rough, is out there for you to read before you ever call us.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Why do third-party standards matter in this trade?</h2>
<p>Garage door work is a trust business. The technician in your garage is working on the heaviest moving object in your home, often near springs under high tension, and most customers have no way to judge the work technically. What you can judge is conduct: punctuality, honesty about what needs fixing and what does not, clean work, and a fair bill. Independent programs like Superpro matter because they verify exactly those things across hundreds of customer interactions, not just the handful a company chooses to advertise. When we recommend a <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair</a> instead of a replacement, or the reverse, the incentive structure behind that advice matters, and public ratings keep everyone honest.</p>
<h2>Does the badge change how we work?</h2>
<p>Honestly, no, and that is the point. We did not change the business to win a badge. The badge recognizes how the business already runs: answer the phone, show up on time, fix it right, charge what we quoted, and stand behind the work. What the program does add is a commitment to keep operating that way, since the status depends on maintaining the standards, not just reaching them once. Consider it a promise with a scoreboard attached.</p>
<h2>What comes next for us?</h2>
<p>Earning the status is not the finish line. The requirements are ongoing, so keeping the badge means keeping the rating, keeping the booking and communication smooth, and keeping every commitment we made to get here. We would rather lose a little time explaining a repair honestly than gain a job by glossing over it, and that approach is what built the rating in the first place. Expect us to keep operating exactly that way.</p>
<h2>Need garage door help from a Superpro team?</h2>
<p>Whether it is a broken spring, a new insulated door, an opener upgrade, or a door that just sounds wrong, we would be glad to earn the next five star review on your job. <a href="/contact-us/">Contact Twins Garage Doors</a> to book online or ask us anything about the work. We will treat your garage like the front door it really is.</p>',
5049 => '<p>The ten most common garage door problems we see are broken springs, doors that will not open or close, misaligned photo eye sensors, noisy operation, doors off their tracks, worn rollers, frayed cables, failing openers, weather seal damage, and remote or keypad issues. Most have clear warning signs, and knowing which ones are do-it-yourself safe can save you money and injury. Here is the full list.</p>
<h2>1. Why do springs top the list?</h2>
<p>Torsion springs carry the door\'s weight, and they wear out from ordinary use. The telltale is a loud bang from the garage, followed by a door that will not lift or feels enormously heavy. Springs are under extreme tension, so this is never a homeowner repair. Stop using the door and book <a href="/garage-door-spring-repair/">spring repair</a>.</p>
<h2>2. What makes a door refuse to open or close?</h2>
<p>The catch-all complaint. Causes range from a dead remote battery to a disengaged trolley, tripped photo eyes, a broken spring, or a failed opener. Start simple: check the wall button, the remote battery, and whether the opener has power, and look for a blinking opener light, which usually signals a sensor issue.</p>
<h2>3. Why does the door reverse before closing?</h2>
<p>Nine times out of ten, photo eye sensors. The two small units near the floor must see each other\'s infrared beam; a bump, cobweb, or dirty lens breaks the link and the opener refuses to close, or reverses immediately. Clear the beam path, wipe the lenses, and gently realign until the indicator lights hold steady. If it persists, wiring or the opener logic needs a professional look.</p>
<h2>4. What causes a noisy garage door?</h2>
<p>Squealing and grinding usually mean dry hinges, rollers, and springs, cured with garage door lubricant twice a year. Rattling points to loose hardware. Banging or scraping deserves attention, since it can signal roller, track, or balance trouble. A door that suddenly gets loud is asking for a tune-up before something breaks.</p>
<h2>5. How does a door come off its tracks?</h2>
<p>Impact is the usual cause, a bumper tap or a bike handle, followed by worn rollers or misaligned track. A door off its tracks can bind, jam, or fall, so stop operating it entirely. This is professional <a href="/garage-door-repair/">repair</a> work, and if the door is stuck open or holding your car hostage, that is what our emergency service is for.</p>
<h2>6. When do rollers become the problem?</h2>
<p>Rollers wear, crack, chip, and wobble with age. Symptoms are jerky travel, dragging on one side, and noise from a specific spot. You can spot bad rollers yourself, but leave replacement to a technician, since several rollers sit in brackets tied to cables under tension.</p>
<h2>7. What do frayed cables mean?</h2>
<p>Lift cables run up both sides of the door and work with the springs to carry its weight. Fraying, slack, or a cable off its drum means the system is one step from dropping a side of the door. Like springs, cables hold serious tension. Look, do not touch, and call for repair.</p>
<h2>8. How do openers fail?</h2>
<p>Openers grind, hum without moving, work intermittently, or die outright. Worn gears, stripped trolleys, failing logic boards, and tired motors are all repairable up to a point. If the unit predates rolling code security and photo eye standards, replacement beats repair. Our <a href="/garage-door-opener-repair/">opener repair</a> team will tell you honestly which side of the line yours is on.</p>
<h2>9. Why does weather seal damage matter?</h2>
<p>The rubber along the bottom and the molding around the sides crack and flatten with age. The signs are daylight around the closed door, drafts, water lines after rain, and debris sifting in. Seal replacement is inexpensive and immediately noticeable, and it protects everything stored inside.</p>
<h2>10. What about remotes, keypads, and wall buttons?</h2>
<p>Dead batteries, lost programming, and worn buttons make up a surprising share of service calls. Reprogramming remotes and keypads is quick, and if a remote was lost or stolen, the opener\'s memory should be cleared and re-paired the same day so the old remote goes dead.</p>
<h2>Which problems are safe to handle yourself?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Safe:</strong> batteries, lens cleaning, gentle sensor alignment, lubrication, clearing debris from tracks, reprogramming remotes.</li>
<li><strong>Not safe:</strong> anything involving springs, cables, bottom roller brackets, or a door off its tracks. Those parts store the door\'s weight as tension and cause real injuries.</li>
</ul>
<h2>How do you avoid most of this list entirely?</h2>
<p>Twice a year, lubricate the moving parts, watch the door run, and test the safety reversal. Once a year, have a professional tune-up that checks balance, tightens hardware, and catches wear early. Most emergency calls we run began as small symptoms months earlier. If your door is showing any of the ten above, <a href="/contact-us/">reach out to Twins Garage Doors</a> and we will sort it before it grows.</p>',
5082 => '<p>To measure for a new garage door you need five numbers: the width and height of the finished opening, the side room on each side, the headroom above the opening, and the backroom depth into the garage. A tape measure and ten minutes gets you close enough for accurate quotes. Here is how to take each measurement like an installer would.</p>
<h2>What tools do you need?</h2>
<p>A tape measure long enough to span the opening, a step ladder, a notepad, and ideally a second person to hold the tape end. A level is handy for checking the floor. Measure in feet and inches, write everything down, and when a measurement falls between marks, record the exact fraction rather than rounding.</p>
<h2>How do you measure the opening width and height?</h2>
<p><strong>Width:</strong> measure the finished opening from jamb to jamb, wood to wood, at the widest point. Take the measurement in three places, near the bottom, middle, and top, because openings are rarely perfectly square. Record the widest figure and note any variation.</p>
<p><strong>Height:</strong> measure from the floor to the underside of the header, again in three spots, left, center, and right. Garage floors slope and settle, so the three numbers often differ. Record the shortest and the tallest.</p>
<p>These two numbers give the nominal door size. Standard residential doors come in common widths for single and double bays, but doors can be ordered in custom sizes, so measure what is actually there rather than assuming yours is standard.</p>
<h2>What is side room and why does it matter?</h2>
<p>Side room is the flat wall space between each side of the opening and the nearest wall, obstruction, or corner. The vertical tracks and their brackets mount in this space. Measure from the edge of the opening to the obstruction on each side separately, since garages are rarely symmetric. Note anything living in that zone: pipes, conduit, electrical panels, shelving. Tight side room does not stop a project, but the installer needs to know before ordering hardware.</p>
<h2>How much headroom do you have?</h2>
<p>Headroom is the space between the top of the opening and the ceiling, or the lowest thing hanging from it. This is where the door curves overhead and where the torsion springs and, usually, the opener live. Measure from the header to the ceiling, and separately note anything that intrudes: beams, ducts, pipes, lights, storage racks, and garage door opener rails from the old installation.</p>
<p>Headroom decides which hardware your door needs. Generous headroom fits standard track. Limited headroom can still work using low headroom track systems designed for tight spaces, and very tall headroom opens the option of high lift track that carries the door further up the wall before curving back. Measure honestly, because this number changes the order.</p>
<h2>What is backroom and how do you measure it?</h2>
<p>Backroom is the depth from the opening back into the garage along the ceiling, the run where the horizontal tracks carry the open door, plus space for the opener. Measure from the inside face of the header straight back, and note obstructions like ceiling storage, furnaces, or attic ladders. As a rule of thumb the door needs its own height plus additional room for hardware and the opener, so a shallow garage is worth flagging early.</p>
<h2>What else should you note while you are out there?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Floor condition:</strong> is the slab level across the opening, or does it dip at one side? A wavy floor affects the bottom seal choice.</li>
<li><strong>What the jambs are made of:</strong> sound wood jambs anchor tracks well, while damaged framing should be repaired during installation.</li>
<li><strong>Power:</strong> is there an outlet near the ceiling for the opener?</li>
<li><strong>The old door:</strong> its size, layers, and any sections that rubbed or bound are useful clues about the opening.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Do your measurements replace a professional measure?</h2>
<p>No, and that is by design. Your numbers are for shopping: they let you compare styles and get realistic quotes, and you can preview door designs on your own home with our <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a>. Before anything is ordered, we confirm every measurement on site, because a door built to the wrong fraction of an inch is a door that seals poorly or does not fit. The final measure is on us, and it is part of every <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> we do.</p>
<p>Measure your five numbers, jot down the quirks, and <a href="/contact-us/">send them to Twins Garage Doors</a>. We will take it from there, from exact sizing to a clean one day install.</p>',
5150 => '<p>Low-headroom garage door systems are hardware kits that let a sectional door operate in garages with very little space between the top of the opening and the ceiling. They rework the track curve and spring placement so the door can turn overhead in a fraction of the room standard hardware needs. If your garage has ducts, beams, or a low ceiling crowding the opening, this is the system that makes a modern door possible.</p>
<h2>What problem does low-headroom hardware solve?</h2>
<p>A sectional door does something tricky at the top of its travel: it changes direction from vertical to horizontal. Standard track makes that turn through a large radius curve, and the door needs clearance above the opening for the curve, plus room for the torsion springs mounted on the header. Older garages, basement garages, and buildings with mechanicals along the ceiling often simply do not have that space. Without a solution, the choices used to be an undersized door, a one piece tilt door, or living with the old setup. Low-headroom systems solve it with smarter geometry.</p>
<h2>How does the double track system work?</h2>
<p>The most common approach uses a second horizontal track. The top section of the door rides in its own dedicated track, while the remaining sections follow the main track. Splitting the duty this way lets the top section begin its horizontal turn almost immediately, without the tall sweeping curve standard hardware requires. The two tracks run parallel back into the garage, and the door stacks neatly overhead just a little lower than it otherwise would.</p>
<h2>What do quick-turn brackets do?</h2>
<p>On the top section, standard rollers sit in fixed positions that assume a big track radius. Quick-turn brackets, also called low-headroom top fixtures, reposition and articulate the top rollers so the section can pivot through the tighter curve earlier and sharper. Combined with the double track, they let the door seal properly against the header when closed and still make the turn in minimal space.</p>
<h2>Where do the springs go when the header is crowded?</h2>
<p>Torsion springs normally mount on the wall above the opening, exactly the space a low-headroom garage does not have. Two solutions exist:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Rear mount torsion:</strong> the spring shaft moves to the back end of the horizontal tracks, deep in the garage, with the cables rerouted to reach the bottom brackets. Same balancing physics, relocated to where the room is.</li>
<li><strong>Extension springs:</strong> springs stretched along the horizontal tracks on each side, an older style that needs no header space at all. They work, but we prefer torsion where possible for smoother, better balanced operation, and extension springs must always run safety cables through their coils.</li>
</ul>
<p>Either way, the springs remain high tension components. Sizing, winding, and adjusting them is professional work, the same as on any door, and our <a href="/garage-door-spring-repair/">spring repair</a> team services both styles.</p>
<h2>What are the benefits of going low-headroom?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>A full size modern door in a space that could not otherwise fit one</strong>, with insulation, new seals, and current safety hardware.</li>
<li><strong>Preserved ceiling space</strong> in garages where every inch matters, since the door stacks close to the ceiling.</li>
<li><strong>Compatibility with openers</strong>, including wall mount openers that skip the ceiling rail entirely, a natural pairing when overhead space is tight.</li>
<li><strong>Normal day-to-day operation</strong>, because once installed, a low-headroom door opens, closes, and seals like any other quality sectional door.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What are the trade-offs to know about?</h2>
<p>Low-headroom hardware has more parts and tighter geometry than standard track, so precise installation matters even more than usual. Track spacing, bracket positions, and spring routing all interact, and small errors show up as binding or uneven travel. Repairs are also slightly more involved for the same reason. None of this is a problem for an experienced installer, but it is a strong argument against improvising the hardware or mixing components from different systems. When something does act up, a <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> visit from techs who know these systems sorts it quickly.</p>
<h2>Is your garage a candidate?</h2>
<p>If you have been told your ceiling is too low for a new door, or your current door was installed undersized to dodge an obstruction, have it measured properly. We check headroom, side room, and backroom, then spec the right combination of double track, quick-turn hardware, and spring placement for the space. Often the garage that could not fit a door fits one fine with the right system. <a href="/contact-us/">Reach out to Twins Garage Doors</a> and we will find the inches your garage has been hiding.</p>',
5151 => '<p>Garage door security has advanced from fixed code remotes that thieves could scan, to rolling codes that change with every press, to smart systems with cameras, alerts, and even fingerprint access. Understanding these layers matters because the garage is one of the largest entry points to your home, and the security of yours depends mostly on which generation of technology is guarding it.</p>
<h2>Why is the garage a security priority?</h2>
<p>Most attached garages open directly into the house, and the connecting door is often unlocked. That makes the garage door, and the electronics controlling it, a primary entrance in every way that matters. It also shelters vehicles, tools, and bikes worth real money on its own. A thief who defeats the garage gets cover from the street and time to work. Securing this door properly protects more than the garage.</p>
<h2>What was wrong with old fixed code openers?</h2>
<p>Early remotes used DIP switches, tiny toggles set to a pattern shared by remote and opener. The pattern was the code, and it never changed. The weaknesses were serious: the number of combinations was small, code grabbing devices could capture and replay a transmitted code, and a patient intruder with a matching remote could cycle through patterns. If an opener from that era is still guarding your garage, it is the weakest lock on your house, and our <a href="/garage-door-opener-repair/">opener team</a> can confirm what you have in minutes.</p>
<h2>How did rolling codes fix it?</h2>
<p>Rolling code technology changed the game. The remote and the opener share a cryptographic algorithm that generates a fresh code on every button press, and each code works only once. Capture the signal and it is already worthless, because the system has moved on. Introduced widely in the 1990s, rolling codes shut down replay attacks and remain the security foundation of every modern opener. Later generations layered on stronger encryption of the signal itself, closing the gap further.</p>
<h2>What do smart openers add to security?</h2>
<p>Connectivity turned the opener from a lock into a monitoring system:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Real time alerts</strong> tell you the moment the door opens or closes, so unexpected activity is known instantly rather than discovered later.</li>
<li><strong>Status checks and remote close</strong> end the did-I-leave-it-open question from anywhere.</li>
<li><strong>Scheduled and automatic closing</strong> fixes the most common real world lapse, the door left standing open.</li>
<li><strong>Built-in cameras</strong> on some openers show live video of the garage with two-way audio, useful for deliveries, kids, and peace of mind.</li>
<li><strong>Access logs and shared access</strong> replace floating spare remotes with revocable app permissions and per-person codes on keypads.</li>
<li><strong>Lock and vacation modes</strong> ignore all remotes while you are away.</li>
</ul>
<h2>Are biometric and keypad systems worth it?</h2>
<p>Wireless keypads have been a practical staple for years: a code on the door frame lets kids in after school without a remote to lose. Newer keypads add fingerprint readers, so access depends on who you are rather than what you know or hold. Biometrics shine where codes get shared too widely or where you want per-person access without managing devices. Treat them as a convenience and control upgrade layered on top of rolling code security, not a replacement for it.</p>
<h2>What physical security still matters?</h2>
<p>Electronics guard the signal, but the door is still a physical object. The fundamentals:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Lock the door between garage and house.</strong> It is your second line, use it.</li>
<li><strong>Protect the emergency release</strong> so it cannot be fished from outside.</li>
<li><strong>Frost or curtain any windows</strong> that put your garage\'s contents on display.</li>
<li><strong>Keep remotes out of parked cars</strong>, or switch to keychain remotes and in-car buttons.</li>
<li><strong>Keep the door closing fully.</strong> A door that reverses before sealing, or sits crooked on worn parts, is effectively unlocked. Mechanical health is security, and that is ordinary <a href="/garage-door-repair/">garage door repair</a> work.</li>
</ul>
<h2>How do you upgrade sensibly?</h2>
<p>Match the fix to your weakest layer. Pre-rolling-code opener: replace it, full stop. Modern opener but no visibility: add a smart bridge or step up to a connected model with alerts and auto-close. Family logistics: add a keypad, biometric if it suits. Habits: fix the visor remote and the unlocked interior door today, for free. If you want a straight assessment of where your garage stands, <a href="/contact-us/">contact Twins Garage Doors</a>. We will tell you which century your opener lives in and bring it up to this one.</p>',
5152 => '<p>Custom garage door design comes down to three decisions: the material, the style, and how the door integrates with your home\'s architecture and technology. Get those three working together and the largest surface on your facade becomes a design feature instead of a blank slab. Here is how we walk homeowners through each choice.</p>
<h2>What materials can a custom door be built from?</h2>
<h3>Steel</h3>
<p>The versatile workhorse. Steel sections take embossed textures, crisp paint finishes, and overlays, and they pair with polyurethane insulation for strength and efficiency. Most custom designs, even ones that read as wood from the street, are built on steel.</p>
<h3>Wood</h3>
<p>Real wood offers what nothing else quite does: genuine grain, stain depth, and full custom shapes. Cedar, hemlock, and mahogany doors can be built to order for historic homes and showpiece facades. The trade-offs are weight, price, and a real refinishing schedule. Wood is for owners who love it enough to maintain it.</p>
<h3>Faux wood composites and overlays</h3>
<p>Molded composite skins and cladding over insulated steel now mimic stained wood convincingly, down to grain texture. You get the carriage house warmth without the upkeep, which is why this category has become our most requested custom look.</p>
<h3>Aluminum and glass</h3>
<p>Full view doors with aluminum frames and glass panels suit modern architecture beautifully, turning the garage into a glowing design element at night. Insulated and obscure glass options manage efficiency and privacy.</p>
<h2>Which styles can you build around?</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Carriage house:</strong> the look of old swing out barn doors, with decorative hardware, crossbucks, and paneling, operating as a normal sectional door.</li>
<li><strong>Modern flush and plank designs:</strong> clean faces, strong horizontal lines, minimal ornament, often paired with long window bands.</li>
<li><strong>Traditional raised and recessed panel:</strong> the classic vocabulary, upgraded through color, texture, and glass into something far beyond builder grade.</li>
<li><strong>Full view glass:</strong> the door as a wall of light for contemporary homes and showroom style garages.</li>
</ul>
<p>Within each style, the real customization happens in the details: panel proportions, window shapes and grilles, hardware, and color. Frosted glass for privacy, arched top sections for character, matte black frames for a modern edge, the combinations run deep.</p>
<h2>How do you integrate the door with your home\'s architecture?</h2>
<p>The garage door often covers a third or more of the street facing facade, so the goal is a door that looks like it was designed with the house, not bolted on after. A few principles we use:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Echo the windows.</strong> Matching the door\'s glass and grille pattern to the home\'s windows ties the facade together instantly.</li>
<li><strong>Coordinate, do not clone, the colors.</strong> Doors matched to trim or siding read composed. A deliberate contrast can spotlight the entry instead.</li>
<li><strong>Respect the home\'s era.</strong> Carriage styles flatter craftsman and farmhouse homes, flush panels flatter modern ones, and mismatches age poorly.</li>
<li><strong>Mind the proportions.</strong> Panel layout and window rows should align with the door\'s size and the facade\'s lines.</li>
</ul>
<p>The easiest way to test all of this is visually. Our <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a> lets you preview materials, styles, colors, and glass on a photo of your own home before anything is ordered.</p>
<h2>What about technology and performance integration?</h2>
<p>A custom door should be as current mechanically as it is visually:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Insulation:</strong> polyurethane cores keep an attached garage moderate, stiffen the sections, and quiet the door. Any custom design worth building deserves an insulated build.</li>
<li><strong>Smart openers:</strong> app control, alerts, automatic closing, battery backup, and camera options integrate the door with the rest of a connected home. Wall mount openers free the ceiling and suit clean modern interiors.</li>
<li><strong>Quiet hardware:</strong> sealed bearing rollers and belt drive operation matter when bedrooms sit above the garage.</li>
<li><strong>Complete sealing:</strong> perimeter weatherstripping and a floor matched bottom seal protect the investment and the comfort behind it.</li>
</ul>
<h2>What does the custom process look like?</h2>
<p>We measure your opening, headroom, and side room, talk through how you use the garage, and narrow the material and style options to what fits the house and budget. You preview the finalists in the <a href="/door-builder/">door builder</a>, we order to spec, and installation with new tracks, springs sized to the door\'s weight, seals, and opener tuning happens through our <a href="/garage-door-installation/">garage door installation</a> team, typically in a day.</p>
<p>Your garage door is the biggest design decision on your facade. Make it deliberately. Call Twins Garage Doors and we will design a door your house looks better wearing.</p>',
];
